{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01YRgaQFc3Jz3JoybnWw8sS3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_0191ZhEnBmDP4cYw86YbxhrU","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Users/rchoi/Personal/mahjong-game/_bmad-output/planning-artifacts/game-architecture.md","offset":601,"limit":600},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13253,"cache_read_input_tokens":9347,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":13253,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":35,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01FRy1xtdzjFuzxBLyNh6fGL","session_id":"e018b2a0-f3f1-40e1-98cc-69fb37f4a59e","uuid":"f2c6d5c2-8d58-4f01-b9aa-db1e035a9e4c"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0191ZhEnBmDP4cYw86YbxhrU","type":"tool_result","content":"601\t  exposure: 'X' | 'C'\n602\t  groups: GroupPattern[]\n603\t}\n604\t\n605\tinterface GroupPattern {\n606\t  type: 'single' | 'pair' | 'pung' | 'kong' | 'quint' | 'sextet' | 'news' | 'dragon_set'\n607\t  tile?: TileRequirement\n608\t  jokerEligible: boolean\n609\t  concealed?: boolean\n610\t}\n611\t\n612\tinterface TileRequirement {\n613\t  color?: string            // \"A\", \"B\", \"C\"\n614\t  value?: number | string   // exact number, or \"N\", \"N+1\", \"N+2\"\n615\t  category?: 'flower' | 'wind' | 'dragon'\n616\t  specific?: TileSpecific\n617\t}\n618\t\n619\ttype TileSpecific =\n620\t  | 'north' | 'south' | 'east' | 'west'       // specific wind\n621\t  | 'red' | 'green' | 'soap'                   // specific dragon\n622\t  | 'any'                                       // any tile in the category\n623\t  | `any_different:${number}`                   // Nth distinct tile (for mixed sets)\n624\t```\n625\t\n626\t**Systems powered by this schema:**\n627\t1. **Mahjong validation** — Does a player's tiles match any hand on the card?\n628\t2. **Hand guidance hints** — Which hands are still achievable? Ranked by closeness.\n629\t3. **Joker exchange validation** — Can this natural tile replace a Joker in this exposed group?\n630\t4. **Scoring** — Point value lookup for the validated hand.\n631\t\n632\t**Yearly update:** Developer encodes new card as JSON each April. Card data integrity test suite validates all hands. Card loaded at game start — never hot-reloaded mid-session.\n633\t\n634\t### Decision 6: Call Window Synchronization\n635\t\n636\t**Approach:** Server-timed window with client freeze broadcast. Freeze is a UX signal, not a fairness mechanism.\n637\t\n638\t**Flow:**\n639\t```\n640\tDiscard happens\n641\t  → Server starts window timer (3-5 seconds per host setting)\n642\t  → Server broadcasts CALL_WINDOW_OPEN to all clients\n643\t  → Clients show call buttons + countdown\n644\t\n645\tPlayer clicks Call\n646\t  → Client sends CALL action to server\n647\t  → Server records call in buffer\n648\t  → Server broadcasts CALL_WINDOW_FROZEN to all clients\n649\t  → All clients show \"Call in progress...\" — no more call buttons\n650\t  → Any in-flight calls (sent before freeze received) still accepted into buffer\n651\t\n652\tCalling player has 5 seconds to confirm\n653\t  → Selects tiles to expose, sends CONFIRM_CALL\n654\t  → Server validates the exposed group\n655\t  → Server resolves ALL buffered calls by priority:\n656\t      1. Mahjong always wins\n657\t      2. Multiple Mahjong calls: all callers must confirm; seat position\n658\t         (closest counterclockwise from discarder) breaks the tie\n659\t      3. Non-Mahjong: closest counterclockwise from discarder\n660\t  → Server broadcasts winning call result as STATE_UPDATE\n661\t\n662\t  OR: Calling player sends RETRACT_CALL\n663\t  → If other calls remain in the buffer, server promotes the next\n664\t    highest-priority caller to the confirmation phase (5-second timer)\n665\t  → If no calls remain, server broadcasts CALL_WINDOW_RESUMED\n666\t    with remaining time; other players can now call\n667\t\n668\t  OR: Confirm timer expires (5 seconds, no CONFIRM or RETRACT)\n669\t  → Server auto-retracts the call on the player's behalf\n670\t  → Same logic as RETRACT_CALL above (promote next caller or reopen window)\n671\t\n672\tAll players pass (or timer expires with no calls)\n673\t  → Server broadcasts CALL_WINDOW_CLOSED\n674\t  → Next player draws from wall\n675\t```\n676\t\n677\t**Wall exhaustion (draw game):** If the wall is empty when a player would draw, the game ends as a draw — no winner, no payments. Server transitions to the scoreboard phase with a `MahjongResult` where `winnerId` is `null`. This is a standard outcome in American Mahjong (\"wall game\").\n678\t\n679\t**Pass tracking:** Server tracks per-player pass status. Discarder auto-passed. Window closes immediately when all 3 non-discarders have responded. No waiting for timer when everyone has acted.\n680\t\n681\t**Latency fairness:** Seat position priority means network speed provides zero advantage. The only theoretical risk — a call arriving after the server timer expires — is negligible at 3-5 second windows.\n682\t\n683\t### Decision 7: Reconnection Strategy\n684\t\n685\t**Approach:** Same protocol as initial join. Full-state model eliminates sync complexity.\n686\t\n687\t**Reconnection flow:**\n688\t1. Connection drops → server marks player as `disconnecting`, starts grace period (~30 seconds)\n689\t2. Server broadcasts `PLAYER_RECONNECTING` to other clients\n690\t3. Player's browser refreshes → SPA loads → reads token from sessionStorage\n691\t4. Client connects WebSocket with `{ roomCode, token }`\n692\t5. Server recognizes token → maps to seat → cancels timer → sends full state + chat history\n693\t6. Server broadcasts `PLAYER_RECONNECTED` to other clients\n694\t\n695\t**Phase-specific fallbacks (if grace period expires):**\n696\t\n697\t| Phase | Fallback Action |\n698\t|---|---|\n699\t| Player's turn | Auto-discard most recently drawn tile |\n700\t| Call window | Forfeit — player's call opportunity lost |\n701\t| Charleston | Auto-pass 3 random non-Joker tiles |\n702\t| Not their turn | No action needed — game already continued |\n703\t| 2+ players disconnected simultaneously | Game pauses entirely — no turns advance, no timers run. If any player is still disconnected after 2 minutes, game auto-ends and transitions to scoreboard with session scores through the last completed game. Threshold: 2 or more seats without an active WebSocket connection at the same time. |\n704\t\n705\t**Why this is simple:** The full-state protocol means reconnection is just \"connect and receive state.\" No delta replay, no event log catchup, no state reconciliation.\n706\t\n707\t### Deferred Decisions\n708\t\n709\tThe following decisions are best resolved during implementation rather than locked in architecture:\n710\t\n711\t- **Project file structure** — Directory organization within each package. Evolves with the codebase.\n712\t- **Error handling patterns** — Client-server error flow and user-facing error UX. Shaped by real error scenarios during development.\n713\t- **Audio channel management** — Priority mixing and channel allocation. Shaped by actual sound asset integration in Epic 7.\n714\t- **No database for MVP.** All state is in-memory (server) or browser storage (client). No PostgreSQL, no SQLite, no ORM. Database selection is deferred to Epic 8 when optional accounts and persistent stats are added. Implementing agents should not set up any database infrastructure.\n715\t- **Deployment provider deferred.** The server requires persistent WebSocket connections and long-running processes, which rules out serverless platforms (AWS Lambda, Vercel Functions, Cloudflare Workers). Compatible targets include VPS (DigitalOcean, Hetzner), containers (Docker on any cloud), or PaaS (Railway, Render, Fly.io). Specific provider chosen at deploy time based on cost evaluation.\n716\t- **No authentication for MVP.** Players are identified by session tokens (Decision 3), not accounts. Authentication (email + Google OAuth) is Epic 8. The session token system is designed as the foundation that auth wraps around when accounts are added.\n717\t\n718\t---\n719\t\n720\t## Cross-cutting Concerns\n721\t\n722\tThese patterns apply to ALL systems and must be followed by every implementation. They are the \"constitution\" that ensures consistency across all AI agent implementations.\n723\t\n724\t### Error Handling\n725\t\n726\t**Strategy:** Three-tier error handling matching the monorepo structure. Result objects for game logic, structured responses for server, friendly UX for client.\n727\t\n728\t**Tier 1 — Game Logic (shared/):**\n729\tErrors are expected outcomes, not exceptions. The validate-then-mutate pattern (Decision 1) returns `ActionResult` with `{ accepted: false, reason }` for rule violations. No try-catch for game rule enforcement. Exceptions are reserved for genuine bugs (null reference, impossible state) which the test suite should prevent.\n730\t\n731\t```typescript\n732\t// CORRECT: Result object for expected game rule violation\n733\tif (state.currentTurn !== action.playerId) {\n734\t  return { accepted: false, reason: 'NOT_YOUR_TURN' }\n735\t}\n736\t\n737\t// WRONG: Don't throw for game rules\n738\tthrow new Error('Not your turn') // Never do this\n739\t```\n740\t\n741\t**Tier 2 — Server (server/):**\n742\t- Fastify's built-in error handling for HTTP routes (room creation, status checks)\n743\t- Top-level try-catch per WebSocket message handler: log the error, send `ServerError` to client, continue running\n744\t- Malformed messages: log at WARN level, drop silently — no crash, no response\n745\t- Room-level error boundary: if a room's state corrupts despite the validate-then-mutate pattern, the room dies gracefully without affecting other rooms:\n746\t  1. Server catches unhandled exception within the room's action handler\n747\t  2. Server logs at ERROR level with full state snapshot for post-mortem debugging\n748\t  3. Server broadcasts `SYSTEM_EVENT` to all clients in the room: `{ type: 'ROOM_ERROR', message: 'Something went wrong. The game has ended.' }`\n749\t  4. Server cleans up the room — removes from active rooms map, closes all WebSocket connections for that room\n750\t  5. Clients show a friendly error screen with session scores through the last completed game\n751\t\n752\t  This is the nuclear option — it should never fire if the test suite is doing its job. But documenting the recovery path ensures an implementing agent knows what to build rather than guessing.\n753\t\n754\t**Tier 3 — Client (client/):**\n755\t- Vue `onErrorCaptured` for component-level error boundaries\n756\t- Global `app.config.errorHandler` logs to console and shows a non-intrusive toast\n757\t- WebSocket disconnects trigger the reconnection flow (Decision 7), not an error screen\n758\t- **No technical error messages to players.** The audience is 40-70+ non-gamers. Errors are either silently handled or shown as friendly language:\n759\t  - \"Reconnecting...\" not \"WebSocket connection reset\"\n760\t  - \"Something went wrong, try again\" not \"TypeError: Cannot read property 'tiles' of undefined\"\n761\t  - The gentle \"nope\" sound (from the GDD audio spec) for rejected actions\n762\t- **Component error boundary strategy:** Log and continue, with escalation for critical failures.\n763\t  - **Non-critical component errors** (chat panel, settings overlay, scoreboard detail): Log via Pino, keep the game running. Most Vue rendering errors are edge cases that resolve on the next `STATE_UPDATE` (arriving within seconds).\n764\t  - **Critical component errors** (rack, discard pool, call buttons, game table): Log via Pino, keep running. If the same critical component errors 3+ times within 10 seconds, trigger a page reload. The reconnection flow (Decision 7) handles recovery — SPA reloads, reads session token from sessionStorage, reconnects to server, receives full state. This matches the \"It Just Works\" reliability pillar from the GDD.\n765\t  - **Never show a \"something crashed\" fallback component** in place of the game table. A broken-looking game table is worse than a quick reload. The reload path is fast (cached assets, instant reconnect) and invisible to other players.\n766\t\n767\t**Errors never pause the game.** The server is authoritative and keeps running. A client error affects only that client. A server error in one room doesn't affect others. The only \"pause\" is the reconnection grace period (Decision 7).\n768\t\n769\t### Logging\n770\t\n771\t**Framework: Pino v9.x** — Fastify's built-in logger. Used on server and client. Shared/ uses a Logger interface with dependency injection.\n772\t\n773\t**Server (server/):**\n774\tFastify initializes with Pino enabled. Child loggers carry room context.\n775\t```typescript\n776\t// Fastify setup\n777\tconst app = fastify({ logger: { level: process.env.LOG_LEVEL || 'info' } })\n778\t\n779\t// Per-room child logger\n780\tconst roomLogger = app.log.child({ roomId: 'MHJG7K' })\n781\troomLogger.info({ playerId: 'uuid-abc', action: 'DISCARD_TILE', tileId: 'bam-3-2' }, 'Player discarded 3-bam')\n782\t```\n783\t\n784\t**Client (client/):**\n785\tPino browser mode maps to `console.*` methods. Same API as server, browser-appropriate output.\n786\t```typescript\n787\timport pino from 'pino'\n788\tconst logger = pino({ browser: { asObject: false }, level: import.meta.env.DEV ? 'debug' : 'warn' })\n789\t```\n790\t\n791\t**Shared (shared/):**\n792\tGame engine accepts a `Logger` interface via dependency injection. Shared/ has zero runtime dependency on Pino — only the type interface. This keeps shared/ as pure TypeScript with no external dependencies.\n793\t\n794\t```typescript\n795\t// shared/types/logger.ts\n796\texport interface Logger {\n797\t  info(obj: object, msg?: string): void\n798\t  warn(obj: object, msg?: string): void\n799\t  error(obj: object, msg?: string): void\n800\t  debug(obj: object, msg?: string): void\n801\t  child(bindings: object): Logger\n802\t}\n803\t\n804\t// shared/engine.ts\n805\timport type { Logger } from './types/logger'\n806\t\n807\texport function createGameEngine(logger: Logger) {\n808\t  return {\n809\t    handleAction(state: GameState, action: GameAction): ActionResult {\n810\t      logger.debug({ action: action.type, playerId: action.playerId }, 'Processing action')\n811\t      // ... validate and mutate\n812\t    }\n813\t  }\n814\t}\n815\t```\n816\tServer passes its Pino instance (which satisfies the `Logger` interface). Client passes the browser Pino instance. Tests pass `{ info() {}, warn() {}, error() {}, debug() {}, child() { return this } }` or `pino({ level: 'silent' })`.\n817\t\n818\t**Log levels:**\n819\t\n820\t| Level | When | Examples | Production? |\n821\t|---|---|---|---|\n822\t| **ERROR** | Something broke that shouldn't | Unhandled exception, corrupted room state, WebSocket server crash | Always on |\n823\t| **WARN** | Handled but unexpected | Malformed client message, rejected action from suspicious client, room timeout cleanup | Always on |\n824\t| **INFO** | Normal operation milestones | Room created, player joined/left/reconnected, game started, Mahjong declared, room cleaned up | Always on |\n825\t| **DEBUG** | Action-level detail | Every validated action, state transitions, call window timing, Charleston passes | Off in production, toggle via `LOG_LEVEL` env var |\n826\t\n827\t**Always log (INFO):** Room lifecycle events, player join/leave/reconnect, game start/end, Mahjong declarations. This is the post-mortem trail for bug reports.\n828\t\n829\t**Never log in production:** Player rack contents. Server logs shouldn't reveal tiles unless DEBUG is explicitly enabled for investigation.\n830\t\n831\t### Configuration\n832\t\n833\t**Approach:** Three tiers matching the monorepo. No YAML config files, no remote configuration, no feature flags. Constants in TypeScript files. Settings in game state. Preferences in localStorage. Environment in `.env`.\n834\t\n835\t| Tier | What | Where | Mutable? |\n836\t|---|---|---|---|\n837\t| **Game constants** | Tile set (152 tiles), group sizes, turn order direction, max players (4), Joker count (8) | `shared/constants.ts` | Never — change requires code change |\n838\t| **Game defaults** | Call window duration (3-5s), grace period (30s), Charleston timeout (60s), chat history cap (100) | `shared/defaults.ts` | Overridable by host settings per room |\n839\t| **Host settings** | Timer mode, call window duration, Joker rules (standard/simplified), dealing style | Room state object, set via host settings panel, broadcast to all clients | Between games only |\n840\t| **Player preferences** | Font size, audio volumes, dark mode override, hand guidance toggle | Pinia `usePreferencesStore` → localStorage | Anytime |\n841\t| **Environment config** | Server port, WebSocket URL, TURN/STUN URLs, log level, debug mode | `.env` files — `process.env` on server, Vite `import.meta.env` on client | Deploy-time only |\n842\t\n843\t```typescript\n844\t// shared/constants.ts — never changes\n845\texport const TILE_COUNT = 152\n846\texport const MAX_PLAYERS = 4\n847\texport const JOKER_COUNT = 8\n848\texport const SEATS = ['east', 'south', 'west', 'north'] as const\n849\t\n850\t// shared/defaults.ts — overridable by host settings\n851\texport const DEFAULT_CALL_WINDOW_SECONDS = 5\n852\texport const DEFAULT_GRACE_PERIOD_SECONDS = 30\n853\texport const DEFAULT_CHARLESTON_TIMEOUT_SECONDS = 60\n854\texport const DEFAULT_CHAT_HISTORY_CAP = 100\n855\t```\n856\t\n857\t**Why no feature flags:** This is a solo-developer MVP with a single deployment. Feature flags add indirection for a benefit (gradual rollout, A/B testing) that doesn't apply. If a feature isn't ready, don't deploy it.\n858\t\n859\t**Environment file structure:**\n860\t```\n861\tmahjong-game/\n862\t  packages/\n863\t    client/.env           # VITE_* prefixed vars (WebSocket URL, feature toggles)\n864\t    client/.env.local     # Local overrides (gitignored)\n865\t    server/.env           # Server vars (PORT, LOG_LEVEL, DEBUG_ENDPOINTS)\n866\t    server/.env.local     # Local overrides (gitignored)\n867\t```\n868\t\n869\t**Security boundary:** Vite only exposes variables prefixed with `VITE_` to the client bundle. Server environment variables (future auth secrets, database URLs, API keys) are never exposed to the browser. An implementing agent must never put sensitive values in `client/.env` or use the `VITE_` prefix for server-only secrets.\n870\t\n871\t### Event System\n872\t\n873\t**Pattern: No custom event system.** The architecture already provides typed communication paths for every scenario:\n874\t\n875\t| Communication | Mechanism | Already Defined In |\n876\t|---|---|---|\n877\t| Client → Server | WebSocket `GameAction` typed union | Decision 2 |\n878\t| Server → Client | WebSocket `StateUpdate` + `ResolvedAction` | Decision 2 |\n879\t| Within client (state changes) | Vue reactivity — components watch `useGameState` and Pinia stores | Decision 1 |\n880\t| Within client (animations) | Watch `resolvedAction.type` on state updates, trigger Motion for Vue | Engine & Framework |\n881\t| Within server | Direct function calls — message handler → `handleAction` → broadcast | Decision 1 |\n882\t\n883\tAdding an event bus or pub/sub layer would create a parallel communication path that duplicates what Vue reactivity and the WebSocket protocol already provide. It would give implementing agents two ways to do the same thing, making data flow harder to trace.\n884\t\n885\t**Animation triggering example:**\n886\t```typescript\n887\t// In a Vue component or composable — no event bus needed\n888\twatch(\n889\t  () => gameState.resolvedAction,\n890\t  (action) => {\n891\t    if (!action) return\n892\t    switch (action.type) {\n893\t      case 'DISCARD_TILE':\n894\t        audioStore.play('tile-discard')\n895\t        // Motion for Vue handles the tile animation via reactive state\n896\t        break\n897\t      case 'DECLARE_MAHJONG':\n898\t        audioStore.play('mahjong-motif')\n899\t        // Celebration sequence triggered by gamePhase changing to 'scoreboard'\n900\t        break\n901\t    }\n902\t  }\n903\t)\n904\t```\n905\t\n906\t**Sound triggering distinction:**\n907\t- **Game-event sounds** (tile discard clack, call snap, Mahjong motif) are triggered by watching `resolvedAction` on state updates — these correspond to server-confirmed game events.\n908\t- **UI-interaction sounds** (button hover, Pass click, tab navigation, chat pop) are triggered directly by Vue component event handlers (`@mouseenter`, `@click`) — these are pure client-side interactions with no server round trip. Both use `useAudioStore` for playback, but the trigger source differs.\n909\t\n910\t### TypeScript Configuration\n911\t\n912\t**`strict: true` in all three package tsconfigs — no exceptions.** This enables `strictNullChecks`, `noImplicitAny`, `strictFunctionTypes`, and all other strict checks. For a game where rule accuracy is a zero-tolerance success criterion, compile-time type safety is mandatory — it catches null references, implicit anys, and type mismatches before they become runtime bugs.\n913\t\n914\tNo `@ts-ignore` without an accompanying comment explaining why the suppression is necessary and what would need to change to remove it.\n915\t\n916\t### Input Sanitization\n917\t\n918\t**All user-provided strings are untrusted.** Chat messages, display names, and reaction content arrive from WebSocket clients and are broadcast to other players.\n919\t\n920\t**Server-side:**\n921\t- Chat messages: capped at 500 characters, stripped of control characters\n922\t- Display names: capped at 30 characters, stripped of control characters\n923\t- Reactions: must match a predefined emoji allowlist — reject anything else\n924\t\n925\t**Rate limiting:**\n926\t- Chat messages: max 10 messages per 10 seconds per player. Excess messages dropped silently (server-side). No error sent — the client's send function is not async, so there's no feedback path needed.\n927\t- Reactions: max 5 per 5 seconds per player. Same drop behavior.\n928\t- Game actions: not rate-limited — the game state machine inherently limits action frequency (one action per turn).\n929\t\n930\t**Client-side:**\n931\t- **All user-provided strings rendered via Vue text interpolation (`{{ }}`) only — never `v-html`.** This is the primary XSS defense. Vue's text interpolation auto-escapes HTML entities.\n932\t- No `v-html` directive anywhere in the codebase unless rendering trusted, developer-authored content (e.g., a static help page). If `v-html` appears in a code review, it must be justified.\n933\t\n934\tThis isn't paranoia — one curious user with devtools open could craft a WebSocket message with a `<script>` tag that renders in other players' chat panels.\n935\t\n936\t### ID Generation\n937\t\n938\tConsistent ID schemes prevent collisions and confusion across implementing agents.\n939\t\n940\t| ID Type | Format | Scope | Generator |\n941\t|---|---|---|---|\n942\t| **Session token** | UUID v4 | Globally unique | `crypto.randomUUID()` on server |\n943\t| **Room code** | 6 alphanumeric (e.g., `MHJG7K`) | Unique among active rooms | Custom generator, collision-checked against active rooms |\n944\t| **Room ID** | UUID v4 | Globally unique | `crypto.randomUUID()` on server (internal, never shown to users) |\n945\t| **Player ID** | `player-0` through `player-3` | Room-unique | Server-assigned sequentially on seat assignment |\n946\t| **Tile ID** | `{suit}-{value}-{copy}` (e.g., `bam-3-2`) | Room-unique | Deterministic from tile definition during wall creation |\n947\t| **Exposed group ID** | `{playerId}-group-{index}` (e.g., `player-2-group-0`) | Room-unique | Server-assigned on group exposure |\n948\t\n949\t**Tile ID convention:** The `copy` suffix (1-4 for regular tiles, 1-8 for Jokers) distinguishes identical tiles. `bam-3-2` means \"the second copy of 3-Bam.\" IDs are generated during wall creation and stable for the game's duration. The pattern matching engine and Joker exchange system reference tiles by these IDs.\n950\t\n951\t### Debug & Development Tools\n952\t\n953\t**Available tools:**\n954\t\n955\t| Tool | What | Activation | Production? |\n956\t|---|---|---|---|\n957\t| **Debug panel** | Collapsible overlay: current game state (JSON), WebSocket message log (last 50), connection status/latency, game phase/turn info, action dispatch helper | `Ctrl+Shift+D` or URL param `?debug=true` | No — `import.meta.env.DEV` only |\n958\t| **Server debug endpoint** | `GET /api/debug/rooms/:code` returns full unfiltered room state | Env var `DEBUG_ENDPOINTS=true` | No — disabled by default |\n959\t| **Multi-seat testing mode** | One browser window controls all 4 seats for testing game loop without 4 browsers | Env var `VITE_DEV_MULTI_SEAT=true` | No — dev only |\n960\t| **Vue Devtools** | Pinia store inspection, component tree, reactivity tracking | Browser extension (auto-detected) | No — stripped in prod build |\n961\t| **Vitest UI** | Visual test runner with Browser Mode for component testing | `pnpm -r test --ui` | No — dev only |\n962\t\n963\t**Production stripping:** All debug features gated behind `import.meta.env.DEV` (client) or env vars (server). Vite tree-shakes dev-only code from production bundles automatically. No debug code ships to players.\n964\t\n965\t**Security notes:**\n966\t- The debug panel's action dispatch helper sends actions through the normal WebSocket path with normal server validation. There is no privileged debug path — the server treats debug-dispatched actions identically to player-dispatched actions. This prevents debug tools from masking validation bugs.\n967\t- The server debug endpoint (`GET /api/debug/rooms/:code`) intentionally violates the information boundary defined in the Security Model — it returns full unfiltered state including all players' racks. This endpoint MUST be disabled in production via the `DEBUG_ENDPOINTS` env var (default: false). It is the single intentional exception to the \"clients never see other players' racks\" rule.\n968\t\n969\t**No cheat commands for MVP.** The debug panel + multi-seat mode + server debug endpoint + direct state inspection covers all development needs. Cheat commands (deal specific tiles, skip Charleston, force Mahjong) can be added if testing demands them.\n970\t\n971\t---\n972\t\n973\t## Project Structure\n974\t\n975\t### Organization Pattern\n976\t\n977\t**Feature-based within each package.** Files grouped by what they do, not by file type. Matches Vue ecosystem conventions and the three-package monorepo.\n978\t\n979\t### Directory Structure\n980\t\n981\t```\n982\tmahjong-game/\n983\t├── packages/\n984\t│   ├── shared/\n985\t│   │   ├── src/\n986\t│   │   │   ├── types/\n987\t│   │   │   │   ├── game-state.ts        # GameState, GamePhase, PlayerState\n988\t│   │   │   │   ├── actions.ts           # GameAction discriminated union\n989\t│   │   │   │   ├── protocol.ts          # ServerMessage, ClientMessage, StateUpdate, etc.\n990\t│   │   │   │   ├── tiles.ts             # Tile, TileId, TileSuit, TileCategory\n991\t│   │   │   │   ├── card.ts              # NMJLCard, HandPattern, GroupPattern, TileRequirement\n992\t│   │   │   │   ├── room.ts              # RoomState, RoomSettings, PlayerPublicInfo\n993\t│   │   │   │   └── logger.ts            # Logger interface\n994\t│   │   │   ├── engine/\n995\t│   │   │   │   ├── game-engine.ts        # createGameEngine(), handleAction()\n996\t│   │   │   │   ├── game-engine.test.ts\n997\t│   │   │   │   ├── actions/\n998\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── draw.ts\n999\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── draw.test.ts\n1000\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── discard.ts\n1001\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── discard.test.ts\n1002\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── call.ts\n1003\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── call.test.ts\n1004\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── mahjong.ts\n1005\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── mahjong.test.ts\n1006\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── charleston.ts\n1007\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── charleston.test.ts\n1008\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── joker-exchange.ts\n1009\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── joker-exchange.test.ts\n1010\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── game-flow.ts\n1011\t│   │   │   │   │   └── game-flow.test.ts\n1012\t│   │   │   │   ├── state/\n1013\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── create-game.ts\n1014\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── wall.ts\n1015\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── wall.test.ts\n1016\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── dealing.ts\n1017\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── dealing.test.ts\n1018\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── scoring.ts\n1019\t│   │   │   │   │   └── scoring.test.ts\n1020\t│   │   │   │   └── validation/\n1021\t│   │   │   │       ├── call-validation.ts\n1022\t│   │   │   │       ├── call-validation.test.ts\n1023\t│   │   │   │       ├── exposure-validation.ts\n1024\t│   │   │   │       ├── exposure-validation.test.ts\n1025\t│   │   │   │       ├── turn-validation.ts\n1026\t│   │   │   │       └── turn-validation.test.ts\n1027\t│   │   │   ├── card/\n1028\t│   │   │   │   ├── pattern-matcher.ts\n1029\t│   │   │   │   ├── pattern-matcher.test.ts  # Exhaustive — all 50+ hands\n1030\t│   │   │   │   ├── hand-guidance.ts\n1031\t│   │   │   │   ├── hand-guidance.test.ts\n1032\t│   │   │   │   ├── joker-eligibility.ts\n1033\t│   │   │   │   ├── joker-eligibility.test.ts\n1034\t│   │   │   │   ├── card-loader.ts\n1035\t│   │   │   │   ├── card-loader.test.ts\n1036\t│   │   │   │   └── card-integrity.test.ts   # Card data validation suite\n1037\t│   │   │   ├── testing/\n1038\t│   │   │   │   ├── helpers.ts            # Test factories: createTestState, buildHand, generateWall\n1039\t│   │   │   │   ├── fixtures.ts           # Pre-built game states for common scenarios\n1040\t│   │   │   │   └── tile-builders.ts      # Convenience functions for tile/group creation\n1041\t│   │   │   ├── constants.ts\n1042\t│   │   │   ├── defaults.ts\n1043\t│   │   │   └── index.ts                     # Public API — single barrel export\n1044\t│   │   ├── data/\n1045\t│   │   │   ├── cards/\n1046\t│   │   │   │   ├── 2026.json\n1047\t│   │   │   │   └── 2025.json               # Previous year (testing only)\n1048\t│   │   │   └── card-schema.json\n1049\t│   │   ├── vitest.config.ts\n1050\t│   │   ├── tsconfig.json\n1051\t│   │   └── package.json\n1052\t│   │\n1053\t│   ├── client/\n1054\t│   │   ├── src/\n1055\t│   │   │   ├── composables/\n1056\t│   │   │   │   ├── useGameState.ts\n1057\t│   │   │   │   ├── useGameState.test.ts\n1058\t│   │   │   │   ├── useHandGuidance.ts\n1059\t│   │   │   │   ├── useHandGuidance.test.ts\n1060\t│   │   │   │   ├── useAudio.ts\n1061\t│   │   │   │   └── useConnection.ts\n1062\t│   │   │   ├── stores/\n1063\t│   │   │   │   ├── preferences.ts\n1064\t│   │   │   │   ├── rack.ts\n1065\t│   │   │   │   ├── audio.ts\n1066\t│   │   │   │   ├── chat.ts\n1067\t│   │   │   │   ├── connection.ts\n1068\t│   │   │   │   └── hand-guidance.ts\n1069\t│   │   │   ├── components/\n1070\t│   │   │   │   ├── game/\n1071\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── GameTable.vue\n1072\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── PlayerRack.vue\n1073\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── OpponentArea.vue\n1074\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── DiscardPool.vue\n1075\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── ExposedGroups.vue\n1076\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── WallCounter.vue\n1077\t│   │   │   │   │   └── TurnIndicator.vue\n1078\t│   │   │   │   ├── tiles/\n1079\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── Tile.vue\n1080\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── TileBack.vue\n1081\t│   │   │   │   │   └── tile-assets/\n1082\t│   │   │   │   │       ├── tiles.svg        # All 152 faces as <symbol> elements\n1083\t│   │   │   │   │       └── tiles.css        # CSS custom properties for suit colors\n1084\t│   │   │   │   ├── actions/\n1085\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── CallButtons.vue\n1086\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── DiscardConfirm.vue\n1087\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── MahjongButton.vue\n1088\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── JokerExchange.vue\n1089\t│   │   │   │   │   └── CallWindow.vue\n1090\t│   │   │   │   ├── charleston/\n1091\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── CharlestonPhase.vue\n1092\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── PassDirection.vue\n1093\t│   │   │   │   │   └── CourtesyPass.vue\n1094\t│   │   │   │   ├── card/\n1095\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── NMJLCard.vue\n1096\t│   │   │   │   │   └── HandHint.vue\n1097\t│   │   │   │   ├── social/\n1098\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── ChatPanel.vue\n1099\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── ReactionBar.vue\n1100\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── SocialOverride.vue\n1101\t│   │   │   │   │   └── TableTalkReport.vue\n1102\t│   │   │   │   ├── lobby/\n1103\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── LobbyView.vue\n1104\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── WaitingRoom.vue\n1105\t│   │   │   │   │   └── PlayerSlot.vue\n1106\t│   │   │   │   ├── scoreboard/\n1107\t│   │   │   │   │   ├── Scoreboard.vue\n1108\t│   │   │   │   