{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0124Txjbg4KnMfq1dEz7boa1","type":"tool_result","content":"1056\t## Epic 3A: Turn Flow & Calling\n1057\t\n1058\tFull calling system with priority resolution, call window freeze, exposure rules, Mahjong declaration with auto-validation, and challenge mechanism. This epic transforms the basic draw-discard loop into real American Mahjong.\n1059\t\n1060\t**Note on parallelism:** Per Cloud Dragonborn — Stories 3A.1-3A.6 (calling mechanics) can begin in parallel with Epic 2 since they don't need the pattern matcher. Only Stories 3A.7-3A.8 (Mahjong declaration/validation) require Epic 2's pattern matching engine.\n1061\t\n1062\t**Note on TypeScript unions:** Each story in this epic extends the `GameAction` and `ResolvedAction` discriminated unions in `shared/types/actions.ts` and `shared/types/protocol.ts` with new action and resolved action types. This applies to all epics that add game actions (3A, 3B, 3C, 4B, 5B).\n1063\t\n1064\t### Story 3A.1: Call Window — Open, Timer, Pass & Early Close\n1065\t\n1066\tAs a **developer**,\n1067\tI want **a call window that opens after each discard with a configurable timer, allows players to pass, and closes early when all players have passed**,\n1068\tSo that **other players have a fair, timed opportunity to claim each discarded tile (FR19, FR20)**.\n1069\t\n1070\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1071\t\n1072\t**Given** a player discards a tile\n1073\t**When** the discard action resolves\n1074\t**Then** a call window opens with state `callWindow: { discardedTileId, discarderId, status: 'open', remainingTime }` and the discarder is auto-marked as passed\n1075\t\n1076\t**Given** an open call window\n1077\t**When** the configurable timer (3-5 seconds, from host settings) expires with no calls\n1078\t**Then** the call window closes, no call is resolved, and the next player in turn order draws from the wall\n1079\t\n1080\t**Given** an open call window with 3 non-discarder players\n1081\t**When** all 3 players dispatch `PASS_CALL`\n1082\t**Then** the call window closes immediately without waiting for the timer (FR20)\n1083\t\n1084\t**Given** a player who is the discarder\n1085\t**When** they attempt to dispatch `PASS_CALL` or any call action\n1086\t**Then** `{ accepted: false, reason: 'DISCARDER_CANNOT_CALL' }` is returned\n1087\t\n1088\t**Given** a player who already passed\n1089\t**When** they attempt to call or pass again\n1090\t**Then** `{ accepted: false, reason: 'ALREADY_PASSED' }` is returned\n1091\t\n1092\t**Given** no call window is open\n1093\t**When** a player dispatches `PASS_CALL` or any call action\n1094\t**Then** `{ accepted: false, reason: 'NO_CALL_WINDOW' }` is returned\n1095\t\n1096\t### Story 3A.2: Call Actions — Pung, Kong, Quint with Validation\n1097\t\n1098\tAs a **developer**,\n1099\tI want **players to call discarded tiles for Pung (3), Kong (4), and Quint (5) groups, with validation that the player has the required matching tiles in their rack**,\n1100\tSo that **the core calling mechanic works for same-tile groups (FR24, FR29)**.\n1101\t\n1102\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1103\t\n1104\t**Given** an open call window and a player has 2 tiles matching the discarded tile\n1105\t**When** the player dispatches `CALL_PUNG` with matching tile IDs\n1106\t**Then** the call is recorded in the call buffer with type `pung` and the caller's player ID\n1107\t\n1108\t**Given** a player has 3 tiles matching the discarded tile\n1109\t**When** the player dispatches `CALL_KONG` with matching tile IDs\n1110\t**Then** the call is recorded with type `kong`\n1111\t\n1112\t**Given** a player has 4 tiles matching the discarded tile (including Jokers as valid substitutes in groups of 3+)\n1113\t**When** the player dispatches `CALL_QUINT` with tile IDs\n1114\t**Then** the call is recorded with type `quint`\n1115\t\n1116\t**Given** a player attempts to call Pung but has fewer than 2 matching tiles\n1117\t**When** dispatching the call action\n1118\t**Then** `{ accepted: false, reason: 'INSUFFICIENT_TILES' }` is returned\n1119\t\n1120\t**Given** a player attempts to call with tile IDs not in their rack\n1121\t**When** dispatching the call action\n1122\t**Then** `{ accepted: false, reason: 'TILE_NOT_IN_RACK' }` is returned\n1123\t\n1124\t**Given** a call action for a pair (2 tiles total including the discard)\n1125\t**When** dispatching the call\n1126\t**Then** `{ accepted: false, reason: 'CANNOT_CALL_FOR_PAIR' }` — pairs cannot be called except for Mahjong (FR28)\n1127\t\n1128\t### Story 3A.3: Pattern-Defined Group Calls (NEWS, Dragon Sets)\n1129\t\n1130\tAs a **developer**,\n1131\tI want **the calling system to support pattern-defined groups from the NMJL card (NEWS = one of each wind, Dragon sets = one of each dragon) in addition to same-tile groups**,\n1132\tSo that **all valid call types on the NMJL card are supported (FR31)**.\n1133\t\n1134\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1135\t\n1136\t**Given** a Wind tile is discarded (e.g., North)\n1137\t**When** a player has the other 3 Wind tiles (East, West, South) in their rack\n1138\t**Then** they can call to form a NEWS group — the call is validated as a legal group\n1139\t\n1140\t**Given** a Dragon tile is discarded (e.g., Red)\n1141\t**When** a player has the other 2 Dragon tiles (Green, White) in their rack\n1142\t**Then** they can call to form a Dragon set — the call is validated as a legal group\n1143\t\n1144\t**Given** a NEWS or Dragon set call\n1145\t**When** validating the group\n1146\t**Then** Jokers can substitute for any tile in the group (groups of 3+), and the group identity is recorded for future Joker exchange validation (FR55)\n1147\t\n1148\t**Given** a player attempts to call a pattern-defined group with incorrect tiles\n1149\t**When** dispatching the call\n1150\t**Then** `{ accepted: false, reason: 'INVALID_GROUP' }` is returned\n1151\t\n1152\t**Given** the call buttons system\n1153\t**When** determining valid call options for a discarded tile\n1154\t**Then** both same-tile calls (Pung/Kong/Quint) AND pattern-defined group calls (NEWS/Dragon set) are included based on the player's rack contents (FR30)\n1155\t\n1156\t### Story 3A.4: Call Window Freeze & Priority Resolution\n1157\t\n1158\tAs a **developer**,\n1159\tI want **the call window to freeze when any player clicks a call, and for the server to resolve all buffered calls by priority (Mahjong > seat position) at resolution time**,\n1160\tSo that **call resolution is fair and deterministic with no fastest-click advantage (FR21, FR22, FR23, FR26)**.\n1161\t\n1162\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1163\t\n1164\t**Given** an open call window\n1165\t**When** any player dispatches a call action\n1166\t**Then** the call window status changes to `frozen`, a `CALL_WINDOW_FROZEN` resolved action is emitted with the caller ID, and no further call buttons are available to other players\n1167\t\n1168\t**Given** a frozen call window\n1169\t**When** additional call actions arrive from other players (sent before they received the freeze)\n1170\t**Then** those calls are still accepted into the call buffer — in-flight calls are not rejected\n1171\t\n1172\t**Given** multiple non-Mahjong calls in the buffer\n1173\t**When** resolving calls\n1174\t**Then** the call closest counterclockwise from the discarder wins (seat position priority, FR23)\n1175\t\n1176\t**Given** a Mahjong call and a non-Mahjong call in the buffer\n1177\t**When** resolving calls\n1178\t**Then** the Mahjong call always wins regardless of seat position (FR21)\n1179\t\n1180\t**Given** multiple Mahjong calls in the buffer\n1181\t**When** resolving calls\n1182\t**Then** the Mahjong call closest counterclockwise from the discarder wins (FR22)\n1183\t\n1184\t**Given** call resolution\n1185\t**When** the winning call is determined\n1186\t**Then** losing callers' calls are silently discarded — no penalty, no notification to the losing caller\n1187\t\n1188\t### Story 3A.5: Call Confirmation, Exposure & Retraction\n1189\t\n1190\tAs a **developer**,\n1191\tI want **the winning caller to confirm their call by selecting tiles to expose within 5 seconds, with the ability to retract if the group is invalid or they made a mistake**,\n1192\tSo that **calls are confirmed with a safety net for misclicks (FR24, FR25, FR57, FR58)**.\n1193\t\n1194\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1195\t\n1196\t**Given** a player wins call priority\n1197\t**When** they enter the confirmation phase\n1198\t**Then** they have 5 seconds to dispatch `CONFIRM_CALL` with the tile IDs to expose from their rack\n1199\t\n1200\t**Given** a valid `CONFIRM_CALL` with correct tiles\n1201\t**When** the confirmation is processed\n1202\t**Then** the called tile + the player's selected tiles form an exposed group, the group is placed face-up in the player's exposed area, the called tile is removed from the discard pool, and the exposed group has a fixed identity recorded (FR55, FR57)\n1203\t\n1204\t**Given** exposed groups\n1205\t**When** attempting to modify them\n1206\t**Then** they cannot be rearranged or broken apart — exposure is permanent (FR58)\n1207\t\n1208\t**Given** a `CONFIRM_CALL` with tiles that don't form a valid group\n1209\t**When** the confirmation is processed\n1210\t**Then** the call is auto-retracted — no dead hand, no penalty (FR25)\n1211\t\n1212\t**Given** a player dispatches `RETRACT_CALL` during the confirmation phase\n1213\t**When** the retraction is processed\n1214\t**Then** if other calls remain in the buffer, the next highest-priority caller enters the confirmation phase; if no calls remain, the call window reopens for remaining time\n1215\t\n1216\t**Given** the 5-second confirmation timer expires with no `CONFIRM_CALL` or `RETRACT_CALL`\n1217\t**When** the timeout fires\n1218\t**Then** the server auto-retracts the call on the player's behalf (same logic as `RETRACT_CALL`)\n1219\t\n1220\t### Story 3A.6: Turn Advancement After Calls (Skip-Ahead)\n1221\t\n1222\tAs a **developer**,\n1223\tI want **play to continue counterclockwise from the caller's seat after a successful call, skipping any players between the discarder and the caller**,\n1224\tSo that **turn order follows NMJL rules after a call (FR13 post-call behavior)**.\n1225\t\n1226\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1227\t\n1228\t**Given** a player successfully calls and confirms a group (not Mahjong)\n1229\t**When** the call resolves\n1230\t**Then** the caller must now discard a tile, and `currentTurn` is set to the caller\n1231\t\n1232\t**Given** the caller discards after a call\n1233\t**When** the turn advances\n1234\t**Then** the next player counterclockwise from the CALLER draws — not from the original discarder\n1235\t\n1236\t**Given** East discards, and West calls\n1237\t**When** the call resolves\n1238\t**Then** South is skipped; West discards, then North draws next\n1239\t\n1240\t**Given** a call where the caller is the next player in turn order (no skip)\n1241\t**When** the call resolves\n1242\t**Then** no players are skipped — play continues normally from the caller\n1243\t\n1244\t**Given** the resolved call action\n1245\t**When** emitting the state update\n1246\t**Then** the `resolvedAction` includes `fromPlayerId` (the discarder) so clients can animate the skip-ahead transition\n1247\t\n1248\t### Story 3A.7: Mahjong Declaration & Auto-Validation\n1249\t\n1250\tAs a **developer**,\n1251\tI want **players to declare Mahjong either from a discard (during call window) or from a self-drawn tile (before discarding), with auto-validation against the NMJL card before revealing to other players**,\n1252\tSo that **the climactic moment of the game is correctly validated and both win paths work (FR64, FR65, FR69)**.\n1253\t\n1254\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1255\t\n1256\t**Given** an open call window\n1257\t**When** a player dispatches `CALL_MAHJONG`\n1258\t**Then** the call is recorded with type `mahjong` and takes priority over all other calls in the buffer (FR21)\n1259\t\n1260\t**Given** it is a player's turn and they have drawn a tile that completes their hand\n1261\t**When** the player dispatches `DECLARE_MAHJONG` before discarding\n1262\t**Then** auto-validation runs against the NMJL card data using the pattern matcher from Epic 2\n1263\t\n1264\t**Given** the player's 14 tiles match a valid hand pattern on the card\n1265\t**When** auto-validation succeeds\n1266\t**Then** the game transitions to `gamePhase: 'scoreboard'`, the winning hand and pattern are recorded in `mahjongResult`, scoring is calculated per Story 2.6, and a `MAHJONG_DECLARED` resolved action is emitted with winner ID, pattern name, points, selfDrawn flag, and discarder ID (if applicable)\n1267\t\n1268\t**Given** a discard Mahjong (from calling another player's discard)\n1269\t**When** scoring is calculated\n1270\t**Then** the discarder pays 2x, other losers pay 1x (FR71)\n1271\t\n1272\t**Given** a self-drawn Mahjong (from the wall)\n1273\t**When** scoring is calculated\n1274\t**Then** all 3 losers pay 2x (FR72)\n1275\t\n1276\t**Given** the Mahjong button\n1277\t**When** checking its availability\n1278\t**Then** it is always available to the player — never disabled or hidden (FR64). The server validates; the client always allows the attempt.\n1279\t\n1280\t### Story 3A.8: Invalid Mahjong Handling & Challenge Mechanism\n1281\t\n1282\tAs a **developer**,\n1283\tI want **invalid Mahjong declarations to be handled with a private warning and cancel option, and a challenge mechanism for disputing validated results**,\n1284\tSo that **honest mistakes are forgivable but confirmed invalid declarations enforce dead hands (FR66, FR67, FR68)**.\n1285\t\n1286\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1287\t\n1288\t**Given** a player declares Mahjong but their tiles don't match any card pattern\n1289\t**When** auto-validation fails\n1290\t**Then** only the declaring player receives a private notification: \"This hand doesn't match a card pattern\" with a Cancel option (FR66)\n1291\t\n1292\t**Given** the player receives an invalid Mahjong warning\n1293\t**When** the player dispatches `CANCEL_MAHJONG`\n1294\t**Then** the declaration is withdrawn with no penalty — play continues as if nothing happened (call window may reopen or turn continues)\n1295\t\n1296\t**Given** the player receives an invalid Mahjong warning\n1297\t**When** the player dispatches `CONFIRM_MAHJONG` anyway (dismissing the warning)\n1298\t**Then** a dead hand is enforced immediately — the player can no longer win or call discards for the rest of the game (FR67)\n1299\t\n1300\t**Given** a Mahjong is auto-validated as valid\n1301\t**When** other players dispute the result\n1302\t**Then** a Challenge button is available during the celebration phase; any non-winning player can tap it within 10 seconds (FR68)\n1303\t\n1304\t**Given** a challenge is initiated\n1305\t**When** the challenge vote opens\n1306\t**Then** all 4 players see the winning hand alongside the matched NMJL card pattern for group review; each player votes Valid or Invalid within 30 seconds\n1307\t\n1308\t**Given** a challenge vote\n1309\t**When** 3 or more players vote Invalid\n1310\t**Then** the Mahjong is overturned — winner receives a dead hand, scoring is reversed\n1311\t\n1312\t**Given** a challenge vote\n1313\t**When** 2 or more players vote Valid (or a player doesn't vote within 30 seconds, defaulting to Valid)\n1314\t**Then** the Mahjong stands and the celebration resumes\n1315\t\n1316\t**Given** the challenge mechanism\n1317\t**When** checking scope\n1318\t**Then** challenges apply ONLY to Mahjong declarations — not to calls, scoring, or other game events\n1319\t\n1320\t---\n1321\t\n1322\t## Epic 4A: Core Multiplayer\n1323\t\n1324\tFour players join a room via shared link and play a synchronized game in real time. Server-authoritative state, WebSocket protocol, session identity, and room lifecycle.\n1325\t\n1326\t**Note on call window sync:** Epic 3A builds the calling logic in the shared/ engine (local). This epic wires all game actions — including call window open/freeze/resolve — over the network via the Action/State protocol. Story 4A.5 explicitly covers call window message types and networked synchronization (AR10).\n1327\t\n1328\t### Story 4A.1: HTTP Room Creation & Room Codes\n1329\t\n1330\tAs a **host player**,\n1331\tI want **to create a game room via an HTTP endpoint and receive a short, human-friendly room code I can share with friends**,\n1332\tSo that **I can invite friends by sharing a link or code over text/voice (FR1, AR7, AR8)**.\n1333\t\n1334\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1335\t\n1336\t**Given** the server is running\n1337\t**When** `POST /api/rooms` is called with `{ hostName: \"Rchoi\" }`\n1338\t**Then** a room is created and the response includes `{ roomId, roomCode, roomUrl, hostToken }` where `roomCode` is 6 alphanumeric characters (e.g., `MHJG7K`)\n1339\t\n1340\t**Given** a room is created\n1341\t**When** `GET /api/rooms/:code/status` is called with the room code\n1342\t**Then** the response includes `{ full: false, playerCount: 0, phase: 'lobby' }`\n1343\t\n1344\t**Given** an unknown room code\n1345\t**When** `GET /api/rooms/:code/status` is called\n1346\t**Then** a 404 response is returned with `{ error: 'ROOM_NOT_FOUND' }`\n1347\t\n1348\t**Given** room codes are generated\n1349\t**When** checking for collisions against active rooms\n1350\t**Then** the generator retries until a unique code is produced — no two active rooms share a code\n1351\t\n1352\t**Given** Fastify is configured\n1353\t**When** the server starts\n1354\t**Then** Pino logging is enabled with child loggers per room (AR13), and the health check endpoint at `GET /health` returns 200\n1355\t\n1356\t### Story 4A.2: WebSocket Server & Connection Management\n1357\t\n1358\tAs a **developer**,\n1359\tI want **a WebSocket server running alongside Fastify that manages connections, enforces message size limits, and detects dead connections via heartbeat**,\n1360\tSo that **real-time communication infrastructure is ready for game state sync (AR4, AR30)**.\n1361\t\n1362\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1363\t\n1364\t**Given** the server is running\n1365\t**When** a WebSocket client connects\n1366\t**Then** the connection is accepted and tracked by the connection manager\n1367\t\n1368\t**Given** the WebSocket server configuration\n1369\t**When** checking settings\n1370\t**Then** `maxPayload` is set to 64KB, and messages exceeding this are dropped before reaching the handler (AR30)\n1371\t\n1372\t**Given** a connected client\n1373\t**When** 15 seconds pass\n1374\t**Then** the server sends a WebSocket `ping` frame; if no `pong` is received within 30 seconds (2 missed pings), the connection is considered dead and closed (AR30)\n1375\t\n1376\t**Given** a malformed WebSocket message (not valid JSON, missing `version` field)\n1377\t**When** the server receives it\n1378\t**Then** it logs at WARN level and drops the message silently — no crash, no response (AR12)\n1379\t\n1380\t**Given** a message with an unrecognized `version` value\n1381\t**When** the server receives it\n1382\t**Then** it responds with `{ type: 'ERROR', code: 'UNSUPPORTED_VERSION' }` and does not process the message (AR4)\n1383\t\n1384\t### Story 4A.3: Room Join via WebSocket & Seat Assignment\n1385\t\n1386\tAs a **player**,\n1387\tI want **to join a game room by connecting via WebSocket with the room code and my display name, and be assigned a seat**,\n1388\tSo that **I arrive at the table ready to play with my friends (FR2, FR7)**.\n1389\t\n1390\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1391\t\n1392\t**Given** a room exists with fewer than 4 players\n1393\t**When** a player connects via WebSocket with `{ roomCode, displayName }`\n1394\t**Then** the player is assigned the next available seat (player-0 through player-3), assigned a wind, and receives the initial lobby state via `STATE_UPDATE`\n1395\t\n1396\t**Given** a room already has 4 connected players\n1397\t**When** a 5th player attempts to connect\n1398\t**Then** the connection is rejected with an error message (5th player handling deferred to Epic 4B)\n1399\t\n1400\t**Given** a player joins\n1401\t**When** other players are in the room\n1402\t**Then** all existing players receive a `STATE_UPDATE` with `resolvedAction: { type: 'PLAYER_JOINED', playerId, playerName }`\n1403\t\n1404\t**Given** a player joins\n1405\t**When** checking the `PlayerPublicInfo` in the state\n1406\t**Then** it includes the player's `displayName`, `playerId`, `wind`, `isHost`, and connection status\n1407\t\n1408\t**Given** player IDs\n1409\t**When** assigned by the server\n1410\t**Then** they are stable for the room's lifetime — `player-0` through `player-3` in seat assignment order (AR6)\n1411\t\n1412\t### Story 4A.4: Session Identity & Token Management\n1413\t\n1414\tAs a **player**,\n1415\tI want **a server-generated session token stored in my browser's sessionStorage that identifies me across reconnections**,\n1416\tSo that **I can refresh my browser or recover from a network hiccup without losing my seat (AR6)**.\n1417\t\n1418\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1419\t\n1420\t**Given** a player joins a room for the first time (no token)\n1421\t**When** the server sends the first `STATE_UPDATE`\n1422\t**Then** it includes a UUID session token that the client stores in sessionStorage\n1423\t\n1424\t**Given** a player reconnects with a valid token\n1425\t**When** connecting via WebSocket with `{ roomCode, token }`\n1426\t**Then** the server maps the token to the player's existing seat and sends full game state\n1427\t\n1428\t**Given** a player opens a second tab with the same sessionStorage token\n1429\t**When** the second connection arrives\n1430\t**Then** the first connection receives `{ type: 'SESSION_SUPERSEDED' }` and is disconnected — one active connection per token\n1431\t\n1432\t**Given** a player closes their browser tab\n1433\t**When** sessionStorage is cleared\n1434\t**Then** the token is gone — a new tab would join as a new player (if a seat is available)\n1435\t\n1436\t**Given** a player refreshes the page\n1437\t**When** the page reloads\n1438\t**Then** sessionStorage preserves the token, and the player seamlessly reconnects to their seat\n1439\t\n1440\t**Given** a tokenless client connects to a room where a seat is in grace period\n1441\t**When** the `displayName + roomCode` matches exactly one disconnected seat\n1442\t**Then** the server reissues a token and restores the player to their seat (token delivery failure recovery)\n1443\t\n1444\t### Story 4A.5: Action/State Protocol & Message Handling\n1445\t\n1446\tAs a **player**,\n1447\tI want **my game actions to be sent to the server, validated, and the resulting state broadcast to all players with per-recipient filtering**,\n1448\tSo that **the game runs with server authority and no client can cheat or see hidden information (AR5, AR10, AR11)**.\n1449\t\n1450\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1451\t\n1452\t**Given** a player dispatches a game action (e.g., `DISCARD_TILE`)\n1453\t**When** the server receives the `ActionMessage`\n1454\t**Then** the server overwrites `playerId` with the session-authenticated player ID (never trusting client-provided IDs), passes the action to the game engine's `handleAction`, and broadcasts the resulting state\n1455\t\n1456\t**Given** a valid action\n1457\t**When** the engine returns `{ accepted: true }`\n1458\t**Then** the server broadcasts `STATE_UPDATE` with the new `PlayerGameView` to each player (filtered per recipient) and includes the `resolvedAction` for animation context\n1459\t\n1460\t**Given** an invalid action\n1461\t**When** the engine returns `{ accepted: false, reason }`\n1462\t**Then** the server sends `ServerError` only to the offending client — no broadcast to others (AR12)\n1463\t\n1464\t**Given** the Action/State protocol\n1465\t**When** checking client rendering behavior\n1466\t**Then** the client renders game state ONLY from `STATE_UPDATE` messages — no optimistic updates, no local prediction (AR5)\n1467\t\n1468\t**Given** a discard triggers a call window\n1469\t**When** the server broadcasts state\n1470\t**Then** all clients receive `callWindow` state including `status: 'open'`, timer info, and the discarded tile — enabling call button display\n1471\t\n1472\t**Given** a player clicks a call and the window freezes\n1473\t**When** the server processes the call\n1474\t**Then** it broadcasts `CALL_WINDOW_FROZEN` to all clients, continues accepting in-flight calls into the buffer, and resolves all calls by seat position priority at confirmation or timeout (AR10)\n1475\t\n1476\t**Given** every WebSocket message\n1477\t**When** checking the version field\n1478\t**Then** all messages include `version: 1` — the shared TypeScript types ARE the protocol spec (AR4)\n1479\t\n1480\t### Story 4A.6: Per-Player View Filtering & Security Test\n1481\t\n1482\tAs a **developer**,\n1483\tI want **the state broadcaster to build per-recipient views that include only the player's own rack and publicly visible information, with an explicit test verifying no rack data leaks**,\n1484\tSo that **the information boundary is airtight — no cheating by inspecting WebSocket traffic (AR31, NFR43)**.\n1485\t\n1486\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1487\t\n1488\t**Given** the state broadcaster function `buildPlayerView(state, playerId)`\n1489\t**When** building a view for player-0\n1490\t**Then** the view includes player-0's rack tiles in `myRack` and does NOT include any other player's rack tiles anywhere in the response\n1491\t\n1492\t**Given** the state broadcaster\n1493\t**When** building views for all 4 players\n1494\t**Then** each view contains: `roomId`, `roomCode`, `gamePhase`, `players` (public info only), `myPlayerId`, `myRack` (only their own), `exposedGroups` (all players — public), `discardPools` (all — public), `wallRemaining`, `currentTurn`, `callWindow`, `scores`\n1495\t\n1496\t**Given** `state-broadcaster.test.ts`\n1497\t**When** running the test suite\n1498\t**Then** there are explicit assertions that for EACH player, no other player's rack tiles appear anywhere in their `PlayerGameView` — this is a hard requirement, not an assumption (AR31)\n1499\t\n1500\t**Given** a spectator view (post-MVP preparation)\n1501\t**When** `buildSpectatorView(state)` is called\n1502\t**Then** no player's rack is included — public information only\n1503\t\n1504\t**Given** the `SHOW_HAND` action during scoreboard phase\n1505\t**When** a player sends `SHOW_HAND`\n1506\t**Then** their full rack is broadcast to all clients — this is the ONLY scenario where rack data is shared, and only during scoreboard phase\n1507\t\n1508\t### Story 4A.7: Game Start & Host Controls\n1509\t\n1510\tAs a **host player**,\n1511\tI want **to start the game when all 4 seats are filled, with the server validating preconditions**,\n1512\tSo that **only the host can initiate the game and only when the room is ready (FR2)**.\n1513\t\n1514\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1515\t\n1516\t**Given** exactly 4 players are connected and the game phase is `lobby`\n1517\t**When** the host dispatches `START_GAME`\n1518\t**Then** the game initializes (dealing, seat/wind assignment), `gamePhase` transitions from `lobby` to `play`, and all players receive the initial game state with their dealt tiles\n1519\t\n1520\t**Given** fewer than 4 players are connected\n1521\t**When** the host dispatches `START_GAME`\n1522\t**Then** `{ accepted: false, reason: 'NOT_ENOUGH_PLAYERS' }` is returned\n1523\t\n1524\t**Given** a non-host player\n1525\t**When** they dispatch `START_GAME`\n1526\t**Then** `{ accepted: false, reason: 'NOT_HOST' }` is returned\n1527\t\n1528\t**Given** the game is already in progress (phase is not `lobby`)\n1529\t**When** `START_GAME` is dispatched\n1530\t**Then** `{ accepted: false, reason: 'WRONG_PHASE' }` is returned\n1531\t\n1532\t**Given** the host starts the game\n1533\t**When** the initial state is broadcast\n1534\t**Then** each player's `STATE_UPDATE` includes their own dealt tiles (via view filtering) and a `resolvedAction: { type: 'GAME_STARTED' }`\n1535\t\n1536\t### Story 4A.8: Room Cleanup & Lifecycle Management\n1537\t\n1538\tAs a **developer**,\n1539\tI want **rooms to be automatically cleaned up when abandoned, idle, or when all players disconnect**,\n1540\tSo that **server memory is reclaimed and stale rooms don't accumulate (AR32)**.\n1541\t\n1542\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1543\t\n1544\t**Given** all players in a room disconnect\n1545\t**When** no player reconnects within 2 minutes\n1546\t**Then** the room is cleaned up — removed from active rooms map, all associated tokens invalidated, memory freed\n1547\t\n1548\t**Given** a game ends (scoreboard phase)\n1549\t**When** no player dispatches `REMATCH` within 5-10 minutes\n1550\t**Then** the room is cleaned up as idle\n1551\t\n1552\t**Given** a host creates a room but no one joins\n1553\t**When** 30 minutes pass with only the host (or zero players)\n1554\t**Then** the room is cleaned up as abandoned\n1555\t\n1556\t**Given** a room is cleaned up\n1557\t**When** checking server state\n1558\t**Then** the room code is released for reuse, all WebSocket connections for that room are closed, and room-level child loggers are disposed\n1559\t\n1560\t**Given** room cleanup occurs\n1561\t**When** a player tries to reconnect with a token from the cleaned-up room\n1562\t**Then** the connection is rejected with `{ error: 'ROOM_NOT_FOUND' }` — the token is no longer valid\n1563\t\n1564\t**Given** multiple rooms are active simultaneously\n1565\t**When** one room is cleaned up\n1566\t**Then** other rooms are completely unaffected — room isolation is maintained\n1567\t\n1568\t---\n1569\t\n1570\t## Epic 5A: Core Game UI\n1571\t\n1572\tA real, usable browser UI — the vertical slice. Players see tiles, draw, discard, call, declare Mahjong, and see scores in a responsive layout. First real 4-player playtest with humans. This epic establishes the design system, builds all core game components, and includes basic audio for playtest personality.\n1573\t\n1574\t**>>> MILESTONE: First 4-player playtest after this epic <<<**\n1575\t\n1576\t### Story 5A.1: Design System Foundation\n1577\t\n1578\tAs a **developer**,\n1579\tI want **the UnoCSS design system configured with all color tokens, typography roles, spacing scale, animation tokens, and accessibility utilities**,\n1580\tSo that **every subsequent UI component is built on a consistent, token-driven foundation with no raw values (UX-DR1 through UX-DR9)**.\n1581\t\n1582\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1583\t\n1584\t**Given** the `uno.config.ts` file\n1585\t**When** reviewing the theme configuration\n1586\t**Then** all color tokens are defined: `felt-teal`, `chrome-surface`, `chrome-surface-dark`, `gold-accent`, `gold-accent-hover`, suit colors (`suit-bam`, `suit-crak`, `suit-dot`), state colors (`state-turn-active`, `state-call-window`, `state-success`, `state-error`, `state-warning`), wall counter states, hand guidance colors, and celebration colors (UX-DR1)\n1587\t\n1588\t**Given** the typography system\n1589\t**When** using named role shortcuts\n1590\t**Then** `text-game-critical` (20px semibold), `text-interactive` (18px semibold), `text-body` (16px regular), `text-card-pattern` (16px monospace/tabular), and `text-secondary` (14px regular) are all available as UnoCSS shortcuts (UX-DR2)\n1591\t\n1592\t**Given** the animation tokens\n1593\t**When** checking CSS custom properties\n1594\t**Then** `--timing-tactile` (120ms), `--timing-expressive` (400ms), `--timing-entrance` (200ms), `--timing-exit` (150ms) are defined with corresponding easing values, and all override to 0ms under `prefers-reduced-motion` (UX-DR3)\n1595\t\n1596\t**Given** the spacing and sizing utilities\n1597\t**When** building interactive elements\n1598\t**Then** the 4px-based spacing scale is available, `min-tap` shortcut produces 44px min-h/min-w, and border radius scale (sm/md/lg/full) and warm-toned shadow scale (shadow-tile/shadow-panel/shadow-modal) are defined (UX-DR4, UX-DR5)\n1599\t\n1600\t**Given** focus ring tokens\n1601\t**When** applied to interactive elements\n1602\t**Then** three context-adaptive variants are available: `focus-ring-on-chrome`, `focus-ring-on-felt`, `focus-ring-on-dark` — all meeting WCAG 3:1 UI component contrast (UX-DR6)\n1603\t\n1604\t**Given** the mood-switching mechanism\n1605\t**When** a CSS class (`mood-arriving`, `mood-playing`, `mood-lingering`) is applied to the root element\n1606\t**Then** mood-aware tokens remap automatically — components built now are mood-ready without modification when Epic 7 adds transitions (UX-DR8)\n1607\t\n1608\t**Given** the `theme.css` file\n1609\t**When** reviewing dark mode support\n1610\t**Then** `prefers-color-scheme: dark` remaps chrome-layer tokens (cream -> charcoal) while felt and gold tokens remain constant (UX-DR1, NFR41)\n1611\t\n1612\t### Story 5A.2: Tile Component & SVG Sprite Sheet\n1613\t\n1614\tAs a **player**,\n1615\tI want **to see beautifully rendered, clearly readable Mahjong tiles that look like premium acrylic tiles**,\n1616\tSo that **I can identify every tile at a glance on both desktop and mobile (UX-DR20)**.\n1617\t\n1618\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1619\t\n1620\t**Given** the SVG sprite sheet\n1621\t**When** checking its contents\n1622\t**Then** all 152 tile faces are defined as `<symbol>` elements with IDs matching the tile ID convention (e.g., `#bam-3`, `#wind-north`, `#joker`, `#flower-a`) (AR18)\n1623\t\n1624\t**Given** the Tile.vue component\n1625\t**When** rendering a tile\n1626\t**Then** it uses `<use href=\"#tile-id\">` to reference the sprite sheet, displays the tile face on a white base with subtle drop shadow and border-radius for the acrylic feel\n1627\t\n1628\t**Given** tile states\n1629\t**When** interacting with tiles\n1630\t**Then** the component supports: default, hover (lifts 4px on desktop), selected (lifts 8px + gold border), disabled (reduced opacity), and face-down (back pattern) (UX-DR20)\n1631\t\n1632\t**Given** tile variants\n1633\t**When** rendering in different contexts\n1634\t**Then** three size variants work: standard (~50px for rack), small (~30px for exposed groups/discards at `tile-min-width`), and celebration (larger for fan-out)\n1635\t\n1636\t**Given** accessibility requirements\n1637\t**When** inspecting tile markup\n1638\t**Then** each tile has `role=\"button\"` and `aria-label` describing the tile (e.g., \"3 of Bamboo\"), and suit is conveyed via shape/pattern in addition to color (UX-DR41)\n1639\t\n1640\t**Given** all suited tiles (Craks, Bams, Dots)\n1641\t**When** rendered at any size\n1642\t**Then** Arabic numeral corner indices are visible for accessibility — experienced players can read Chinese characters, newcomers need the number\n1643\t\n1644\t### Story 5A.3: TileRack with Drag-and-Drop & Sort\n1645\t\n1646\tAs a **player**,\n1647\tI want **to see my hand of 13-14 tiles in a horizontal row that I can rearrange by dragging and sort with one tap**,\n1648\tSo that **I can organize my tiles the way I think about my hand (FR120, FR121, UX-DR21)**.\n1649\t\n1650\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1651\t\n1652\t**Given** the TileRack component\n1653\t**When** rendering a player's hand\n1654\t**Then** all tiles display in a horizontal row at standard size (~50px), with the rack anchored at the bottom of the game table\n1655\t\n1656\t**Given** a player drags a tile\n1657\t**When** the drag exceeds the 10px dead zone threshold\n1658\t**Then** the tile enters drag mode with Vue DnD Kit, shows visual feedback during drag, and snaps to the new position on drop (UX-DR42, AR22)\n1659\t\n1660\t**Given** a player taps a tile (movement under 10px threshold)\n1661\t**When** the tap is detected\n1662\t**Then** it registers as a selection (tile lifts), not a drag — preventing accidental rack rearrangement (UX-DR42)\n1663\t\n1664\t**Given** the Sort button\n1665\t**When** tapped\n1666\t**Then** tiles reorder by suit (Bam, Crak, Dot) then by number within suit, with winds, dragons, flowers, and jokers grouped at the end (FR121)\n1667\t\n1668\t**Given** a phone viewport where 13-14 tiles would shrink below 30px\n1669\t**When** rendering the rack\n1670\t**Then** tiles maintain minimum 30px width and the rack scrolls horizontally instead of shrinking (UX-DR15)\n1671\t\n1672\t**Given** keyboard navigation\n1673\t**When** the rack has focus\n1674\t**Then** Arrow keys move between tiles, Enter selects/deselects a tile, and the rack is a `role=\"list\"` with tile children as `role=\"listitem\"` (UX-DR21, UX-DR43)\n1675\t\n1676\t**Given** rack state\n1677\t**When** it is NOT the player's turn\n1678\t**Then** tiles are visible but not selectable (passive state) — no lift on tap, no drag enabled\n1679\t\n1680\t### Story 5A.4: Game Table Layout (Immersive Table)\n1681\t\n1682\tAs a **player**,\n1683\tI want **a full-width felt game table with my rack at the bottom, opponents at cardinal positions, and a central area for discards and wall counter**,\n1684\tSo that **it feels like sitting at a real Mahjong table with friends (UX-DR10, UX-DR11)**.\n1685\t\n1686\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1687\t\n1688\t**Given** the GameTable layout on iPad landscape (1024px, primary target)\n1689\t**When** rendering the game view\n1690\t**Then** the felt surface is full-width (no persistent sidebar), the player's rack anchors the bottom, opponent areas are at top/left/right positions, and the central area contains discard pools and wall counter (UX-DR10)\n1691\t\n1692\t**Given** opponent areas\n1693\t**When** rendering player presence\n1694\t**Then** each opponent position shows: avatar circle with player initial and name, connection status dot, and their exposed groups below — using the same space whether video is present or not (UX-DR23)\n1695\t\n1696\t**Given** a desktop viewport (>1024px)\n1697\t**When** rendering\n1698\t**Then** the layout uses extra space for larger video frame placeholders and more generous spacing — not a stretched tablet layout\n1699\t\n1700\t**Given** a phone viewport (<768px)\n1701\t**When** rendering\n1702\t**Then** opponent areas compress to small avatars (~40px), discard pools compress, and a bottom bar appears for future NMJL/chat/A/V toggles\n1703\t\n1704\t**Given** the felt table center area\n1705\t**When** checking minimum height\n1706\t**Then** it occupies at least 40% of viewport height on all devices (UX-DR16)\n1707\t\n1708\t**Given** device orientation change\n1709\t**When** rotating the device mid-game\n1710\t**Then** the layout adapts fluidly with no game state loss, no modal interruptions, and panel state preserved (UX-DR18)\n1711\t\n1712\t**Given** mobile safe areas\n1713\t**When** rendering fixed-bottom elements (rack, bottom bar)\n1714\t**Then** `padding-bottom: env(safe-area-inset-bottom)` is applied to avoid overlap with iPhone home indicator (UX-DR19)\n1715\t\n1716\t**Given** the action zone above the rack\n1717\t**When** defining the layout region\n1718\t**Then** a fixed-size container component (\"ActionZone\") is created that houses call buttons, discard confirm, and Mahjong button — it maintains fixed dimensions regardless of content, never resizes or repositions, and buttons center within it (UX-DR13). This is the single location for all player action buttons across all game states.\n1719\t\n1720\t**Given** game table regions (opponent areas, discard pools, action zone)\n1721\t**When** building the layout in this story\n1722\t**Then** regions are implemented as placeholder containers with correct sizing and positioning — subsequent stories (5A.5 discard pool, 5A.6 call buttons, 5A.8 turn indicator) populate these regions with real components. The layout scaffold ships first; components plug in after.\n1723\t\n1724\t### Story 5A.5: Discard Pool & Two-Step Discard Interaction\n1725\t\n1726\tAs a **player**,\n1727\tI want **to discard tiles with a clear two-step interaction (select then confirm) and see all players' discards arranged in chronological rows at each seat**,\n1728\tSo that **discarding feels rhythmic and safe, and I can read the table to track what's been played (FR17, FR122, UX-DR13)**.\n1729\t\n1730\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1731\t\n1732\t**Given** it is my turn and I have drawn a tile\n1733\t**When** I tap a tile in my rack\n1734\t**Then** the tile lifts (selected state, 8px + gold border) and a \"Discard\" confirm button appears in the fixed action zone above my rack (UX-DR13)\n1735\t\n1736\t**Given** the confirm button\n1737\t**When** checking its position\n1738\t**Then** it appears in the fixed action zone — the same zone where call buttons will appear — and the zone maintains fixed size regardless of content (UX-DR13)\n1739\t\n1740\t**Given** I tap the \"Discard\" confirm button\n1741\t**When** the discard action is sent to the server and confirmed\n1742\t**Then** the tile animates from my rack to my discard pool with the tactile timing token (120ms), a tile clack sound plays, and the turn indicator moves to the next player\n1743\t\n1744\t**Given** I have selected a tile but tap a different tile instead\n1745\t**When** the second tap registers\n1746\t**Then** the first tile deselects (lowers) and the second tile selects (lifts) — only one tile selected at a time\n1747\t\n1748\t**Given** each player's discard pool\n1749\t**When** tiles are discarded throughout the game\n1750\t**Then** discards display in front of the respective player's seat in chronological rows matching physical play layout (FR122)\n1751\t\n1752\t**Given** the most recently discarded tile\n1753\t**When** it lands in the discard pool\n1754\t**Then** it gets a brief gold pulse animation to draw attention (latest-discard state)\n1755\t\n1756\t**Given** immediate acknowledgment\n1757\t**When** I tap a tile\n1758\t**Then** the lift animation starts instantly (120ms, timing-tactile) BEFORE the server confirms — this is acknowledgment, not optimistic update (UX-DR31)\n1759\t\n1760\t### Story 5A.6: Action Zone & Call Buttons\n1761\t\n1762\tAs a **player**,\n1763\tI want **call buttons to appear instantly in a fixed position during the call window, showing only my valid call options**,\n1764\tSo that **I can react quickly during the 3-5 second window without hunting for buttons (FR30, UX-DR22, UX-DR30)**.\n1765\t\n1766\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1767\t\n1768\t**Given** a tile is discarded by another player and a call window opens\n1769\t**When** I have valid call options\n1770\t**Then** only the valid call buttons appear (e.g., \"Pung\" if I can Pung, \"Mahjong\" if applicable) — no grayed-out buttons for invalid calls. A \"Pass\" button is always shown. (UX-DR22, UX-DR30)\n1771\t\n1772\t**Given** I have no valid calls\n1773\t**When** the call window opens\n1774\t**Then** only the \"Pass\" button appears in the action zone\n1775\t\n1776\t**Given** the action zone\n1777\t**When** checking its behavior across states\n1778\t**Then** it maintains a FIXED height and width regardless of how many buttons are displayed — buttons center within the zone, the zone never resizes or repositions (UX-DR13)\n1779\t\n1780\t**Given** call buttons\n1781\t**When** checking styling\n1782\t**Then** call buttons (Pung, Kong, Quint) use the Urgent tier (call-window fill, white text, text-game-critical sizing) and Pass uses Secondary tier (chrome fill, border) (UX-DR30)\n1783\t\n1784\t**Given** phone viewport (<768px) with 4+ call options simultaneously\n1785\t**When** rendering call buttons\n1786\t**Then** buttons stack in a 2x2 grid within the fixed action zone (UX-DR14)\n1787\t\n1788\t**Given** the call window opens\n1789\t**When** checking accessibility\n1790\t**Then** `aria-live=\"assertive\"` announces the call window, auto-focus moves to the first call button for keyboard users, and all buttons meet 44px minimum height (UX-DR22)\n1791\t\n1792\t**Given** the call window closes (all pass, timer expires, or call resolved)\n1793\t**When** buttons disappear\n1794\t**Then** they exit with the exit animation token (150ms, ease-in) and the action zone returns to showing only the Mahjong button\n1795\t\n1796\t### Story 5A.7: Mahjong Button & Declaration UI\n1797\t\n1798\tAs a **player**,\n1799\tI want **a persistent Mahjong button in a fixed position that I can always tap, triggering auto-validation with clear feedback**,\n1800\tSo that **declaring Mahjong is confident and unmissable — the climactic moment of the game (FR64, UX-DR30)**.\n1801\t\n1802\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1803\t\n1804\t**Given** any game state (my turn, not my turn, call window open or closed)\n1805\t**When** viewing the action zone\n1806\t**Then** the Mahjong button is always visible in its fixed position — never hidden, never disabled (FR64)\n1807\t\n1808\t**Given** the Mahjong button styling\n1809\t**When** checking its appearance\n1810\t**Then** it uses Primary tier (gold accent fill, dark text, text-game-critical sizing) and is the ONE primary button on screen during normal play (UX-DR30)\n1811\t\n1812\t**Given** I tap the Mahjong button during a call window\n1813\t**When** checking call behavior\n1814\t**Then** a `CALL_MAHJONG` action is dispatched and takes priority over all other calls\n1815\t\n1816\t**Given** I tap the Mahjong button on my turn (before discarding)\n1817\t**When** I've drawn a tile that completes my hand\n1818\t**Then** a `DECLARE_MAHJONG` action is dispatched for self-drawn Mahjong\n1819\t\n1820\t**Given** a valid Mahjong declaration\n1821\t**When** the server confirms\n1822\t**Then** the game transitions to scoreboard phase, the scoring breakdown is displayed, and the Mahjong signature motif sound plays\n1823\t\n1824\t**Given** an invalid Mahjong declaration\n1825\t**When** the server returns the private warning\n1826\t**Then** only I see an inline notification with a \"Cancel\" option — other players see nothing (FR66, UX-DR35's private-first principle)\n1827\t\n1828\t**Given** keyboard navigation\n1829\t**When** the Mahjong button has focus\n1830\t**Then** Enter or Space activates it, and it has `aria-label=\"Declare Mahjong\"`\n1831\t\n1832\t### Story 5A.8: Turn Indicator, Wall Counter & Game Scoreboard\n1833\t\n1834\tAs a **player**,\n1835\tI want **to always know whose turn it is, how many tiles remain in the wall, and the current game score**,\n1836\tSo that **I can read the game state at a glance from across the room on a propped-up iPad (UX-DR24)**.\n1837\t\n1838\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1839\t\n1840\t**Given** the current turn\n1841\t**When** viewing the game table\n1842\t**Then** the active player's seat area has a `state-turn-active` warm glow that is visible from across the room on iPad, and a turn indicator badge shows the player's name\n1843\t\n1844\t**Given** the wall counter\n1845\t**When** viewing the game table\n1846\t**Then** \"Wall: NN\" is displayed at the top center of the felt area, visible to all players throughout the game (FR100)\n1847\t\n1848\t**Given** the wall counter state\n1849\t**When** tiles remain above 20\n1850\t**Then** it displays in `wall-normal` neutral styling\n1851\t\n1852\t**Given** the wall counter\n1853\t**When** tiles drop to 20 or fewer\n1854\t**Then** it transitions to `wall-warning` amber styling, and `aria-live=\"polite\"` announces the state change (UX-DR24)\n1855\t\n1856\t**Given** the wall counter\n1857\t**When** tiles drop to 10 or fewer\n1858\t**Then** it transitions to `wall-critical` stronger urgency styling with another polite announcement\n1859\t\n1860\t**Given** the game-level scoreboard\n1861\t**When** viewing during play\n1862\t**Then** each player's current session score is visible (compact display) near their seat area or in a summary bar\n1863\t\n1864\t**Given** a game ends (Mahjong or wall game)\n1865\t**When** transitioning to scoreboard phase\n1866\t**Then** the full scoring breakdown is displayed — winner's hand value, payment amounts per player, and updated session totals (FR75)\n1867\t\n1868\t**Given** a call resolves and play skips ahead (e.g., East discards, West calls, South is skipped)\n1869\t**When** the turn indicator transitions\n1870\t**Then** the indicator visually narrates the skip — briefly passing over skipped seats before landing on the caller's seat, so all players understand why the turn jumped (UX-DR32 skip-ahead visualization). Uses `timing-expressive` (400ms) for the transition.\n1871\t\n1872\t### Story 5A.9: Keyboard Navigation & Accessibility Foundation\n1873\t\n1874\tAs a **player using keyboard or assistive technology**,\n1875\tI want **full keyboard navigation with Tab zones, arrow key movement, and visible focus indicators on every interactive element**,\n1876\tSo that **the game is playable without a mouse and the accessibility foundation is solid from day one (FR119, UX-DR43, NFR31)**.\n1877\t\n1878\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1879\t\n1880\t**Given** the game table is loaded\n1881\t**When** pressing Tab\n1882\t**Then** focus cycles through zones in order: Rack -> Action buttons -> Chat (placeholder) -> Controls, with a visible gold focus ring (2px solid, 2px offset) on the focused element (UX-DR6, UX-DR43)\n1883\t\n1884\t**Given** focus is in the Rack zone\n1885\t**When** pressing Arrow keys\n1886\t**Then** focus moves between individual tiles; Enter selects/deselects the focused tile\n1887\t\n1888\t**Given** focus is in the Action zone\n1889\t**When** pressing Arrow keys\n1890\t**Then** focus moves between available buttons (call buttons, Mahjong, Pass); Enter activates the focused button\n1891\t\n1892\t**Given** focus is in the chat input (placeholder for Epic 6A)\n1893\t**When** pressing Escape\n1894\t**Then** focus exits the chat area and returns to the game zones (FR119)\n1895\t\n1896\t**Given** the page loads\n1897\t**When** pressing Tab before interacting\n1898\t**Then** a \"Skip to game table\" link appears (visible only on Tab focus) that jumps past chrome to the rack/action area\n1899\t\n1900\t**Given** all interactive elements\n1901\t**When** inspecting markup\n1902\t**Then** every button has semantic HTML (`<button>`), appropriate `aria-label`, and the focus ring uses the context-adaptive token (on-chrome, on-felt, or on-dark depending on background)\n1903\t\n1904\t**Given** `prefers-reduced-motion` is active\n1905\t**When** interacting with any element\n1906\t**Then** all animations resolve to 0ms — no motion anywhere in the application (UX-DR3, NFR28)\n1907\t\n1908\t### Story 5A.10: Shared Primitive Extraction & Tile Readability Validation\n1909\t\n1910\tAs a **developer**,\n1911\tI want **to extract shared UI primitives from the components built in this epic and validate tile readability at minimum size with the target demographic**,\n1912\tSo that **the component library is DRY and tiles are proven readable before dependent epics build on them (UX-DR39, UX-DR40, UX-DR45)**.\n1913\t\n1914\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n1915\t\n1916\t**Given** the components built in Stories 5A.2-5A.9\n1917\t**When** reviewing for shared patterns\n1918\t**Then** the following primitives are extracted: BaseButton (44px min, press states, focus ring, tier styling), BasePanel (consistent bg/border/shadow/radius), BaseBadge (turn indicator, wall counter, status dot), BaseToast (enter/exit animation, auto-dismiss, positioning) (UX-DR39)\n1919\t\n1920\t**Given** extracted primitives\n1921\t**When** refactoring existing components to use them\n1922\t**Then** all components from this epic use the shared primitives — no duplicate button/panel/badge implementations remain\n1923\t\n1924\t**Given** tile readability validation\n1925\t**When** all 152 tile faces are rendered at 30px width (`tile-min-width`)\n1926\t**Then** suit symbols, Arabic corner numerals, and tile identity are clearly distinguishable — validated by at least one person from the target demographic (40-70+) or by the developer's honest assessment at arm's length on an iPad (UX-DR45)\n1927\t\n1928\t**Given** tile readability fails at 30px\n1929\t**When** corner indices or suit symbols are not clearly readable\n1930\t**Then** `tile-min-width` is bumped to 32px or 34px and all dependent components (DiscardPool, ExposedGroups, celebration fan-out) are updated before this epic closes\n1931\t\n1932\t**Given** the primitive extraction\n1933\t**When** checking for components NOT yet needed\n1934\t**Then** BaseOverlay, BaseInput, BaseToggle, BaseSelect, BaseNumberStepper, and MobileBottomBar are NOT extracted yet — they'll be extracted when their consumer epics (3B, 5B, 6A) build the first component that needs them (UX-DR40)\n1935\t\n1936\t---\n1937\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_013LARjtB1XKZ8zCa7VSrMaH","session_id":"e018b2a0-f3f1-40e1-98cc-69fb37f4a59e","uuid":"1b3d4c29-c59f-4f05-8579-f367724bc144","timestamp":"2026-03-28T03:09:07.750Z"}
