{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AP2JKqS17BGRpFDqRWdC3h","type":"tool_result","content":"1000\t**Key UX moments:**\n1001\t- **Call buttons appear instantly** in the fixed action zone — same spot every time (P4: same place, every time).\n1002\t- **Only valid calls shown** — no grayed-out buttons. If you can Pung, you see \"Pung.\" If you can't call, you see \"Pass.\"\n1003\t- **Freeze on click** — the moment any player clicks a call, the window freezes for everyone. No \"fastest click\" advantage; seat position resolves ties.\n1004\t- **Call resolution narration** — all non-calling players see who called what and why they won priority: \"Sarah called Pung — resolving...\" or \"Sarah called Pung, Linda called Kong — Linda wins (closer in seat order).\" This satisfies Emotional Design Principle #3 (\"the system always shows its work\") and prevents \"what just happened?\" confusion.\n1005\t- **Confirmation phase is the safety net** — select tiles from rack, confirm exposure. Retraction allowed here with no penalty. This is the \"Confirm before consequence\" principle at work.\n1006\t- **Point of no return** — once tiles are placed into the exposed area, the call is irretractable. The confirmation step carries the full weight.\n1007\t- **Skip-ahead rule** — after a call, play continues counterclockwise from the caller. Players in between are skipped. The UI must visually narrate this transition.\n1008\t\n1009\t---\n1010\t\n1011\t### 4. Charleston Flow\n1012\t\n1013\tThe peak social moment. All four players active simultaneously. Must feel alive and social, not like filling out a form.\n1014\t\n1015\t```mermaid\n1016\tflowchart TD\n1017\t    A[Charleston begins after dealing] --> B[\"FIRST CHARLESTON (mandatory)\"]\n1018\t    B --> C[\"Pass 1: RIGHT — Select 3 tiles to pass right\"]\n1019\t    C --> C1[Direction indicator shows RIGHT arrow]\n1020\t    C1 --> C2[\"Select 3 tiles from rack (progress: '2 of 3 selected')\"]\n1021\t    C2 --> C3[Tap 'Pass' button]\n1022\t    C3 --> C4[Tiles animate to right neighbor — receive 3 from left]\n1023\t    C4 --> D[\"Pass 2: ACROSS — Select 3 tiles to pass across\"]\n1024\t    D --> D1[Direction indicator shows ACROSS arrow]\n1025\t    D1 --> D2[Select 3 tiles, tap Pass]\n1026\t    D2 --> D3[Tiles animate across — receive 3 from across]\n1027\t    D3 --> E[\"Pass 3: LEFT — BLIND PASS enforced\"]\n1028\t    E --> E1[\"Must select 3 tiles BEFORE seeing Across tiles\"]\n1029\t    E1 --> E2[Select 3 tiles while Across tiles are hidden]\n1030\t    E2 --> E3[\"Tap Pass — held beat of anticipation — THEN Across tiles revealed\"]\n1031\t    E3 --> E4[Tiles animate left — receive 3 from right]\n1032\t    E4 --> F[\"SECOND CHARLESTON — Unanimous vote\"]\n1033\t    F --> G[\"Prompt: 'Do a second Charleston?' — All 4 must agree\"]\n1034\t    G -->|Any player declines| H[Skip to Courtesy Pass]\n1035\t    G -->|All agree| I[\"SECOND CHARLESTON (reversed direction)\"]\n1036\t    I --> I1[\"Pass 1: LEFT\"]\n1037\t    I1 --> I2[\"Pass 2: ACROSS\"]\n1038\t    I2 --> I3[\"Pass 3: RIGHT — BLIND PASS enforced\"]\n1039\t    I3 --> H\n1040\t    H --> J[\"COURTESY PASS (optional) — with player across\"]\n1041\t    J --> K[\"Each player independently selects 0-3 tiles\"]\n1042\t    K --> L{\"Counts match?\"}\n1043\t    L -->|Yes| M[Swap that many tiles simultaneously]\n1044\t    L -->|No| N[\"Lower count used — narrated: 'Linda wanted 3, Sarah wanted 2 — passing 2 each'\"]\n1045\t    N --> M\n1046\t    M --> O[Charleston complete — first turn begins]\n1047\t    O --> P[\"East evaluates 14 tiles and discards (no draw)\"]\n1048\t```\n1049\t\n1050\t**Emotional pacing beats per pass:**\n1051\t- **Right pass:** Nervous excitement — quick, anticipatory\n1052\t- **Across pass:** Strategic evaluation — players study what they received\n1053\t- **Left/blind pass:** Peak tension — a held beat after tiles are selected but before the reveal, since players chose blind. The reveal of Across tiles after the blind selection deserves a moment of anticipation\n1054\t- **Second Charleston vote:** Brief social negotiation — conversational pause\n1055\t- **Courtesy pass:** Intimate one-on-one — gentler pacing, the Charleston is winding down\n1056\t\n1057\tNot all passes are equal. The developer should build in slightly more breathing room at the blind pass reveal and courtesy pass moments.\n1058\t\n1059\t**Key UX moments:**\n1060\t- **Direction indicator** always visible and bold — players must always know which way tiles are going.\n1061\t- **Blind pass enforcement** — the UI physically prevents seeing Across tiles until Left pass tiles are selected. This is a rule, not a suggestion.\n1062\t- **Tile selection uses shared TileSelectionAction pattern** — progress indicator (\"2 of 3 selected\"), confirm/cancel, same interaction for Charleston, call confirmation, and Joker exchange.\n1063\t- **Social time** — voice chat, reactions, and text chat are fully active throughout. This is prime social energy. The UI must NOT block social features during Charleston.\n1064\t- **Courtesy pass negotiation** — the lower-count resolution is automatic, transparent, and narrated.\n1065\t- **Disconnect handling** — 30-second grace period, then auto-pass 3 random non-Joker tiles. Gentle, preserves game flow.\n1066\t\n1067\t---\n1068\t\n1069\t### 5. Mahjong Declaration Flow\n1070\t\n1071\tTHE moment. Two paths: discard Mahjong (calling someone's discard) and self-drawn Mahjong (drawing the winning tile from the wall).\n1072\t\n1073\t```mermaid\n1074\tflowchart TD\n1075\t    A{How was Mahjong triggered?} -->|Discard completes hand| B[Player taps Mahjong during call window]\n1076\t    A -->|Drawn tile completes hand| C[Player taps Mahjong button before discarding]\n1077\t    B --> D[Call window FREEZES]\n1078\t    D --> E{Multiple Mahjong calls?}\n1079\t    E -->|Yes| F[Priority: closest counterclockwise from discarder]\n1080\t    E -->|No| G[Single Mahjong call proceeds]\n1081\t    F --> G\n1082\t    C --> G\n1083\t    G --> H[\"Auto-validation runs against NMJL card data (before reveal)\"]\n1084\t    H --> I{Hand valid?}\n1085\t    I -->|Invalid| J[\"Private notification: 'This hand doesn't match a card pattern'\"]\n1086\t    J --> K{Player chooses?}\n1087\t    K -->|Cancel — back out| L[Mahjong cancelled — no penalty, play continues]\n1088\t    K -->|Confirm anyway| M[\"Dead hand enforced — player continues but cannot win or call\"]\n1089\t    I -->|Valid| N{Concealed hand check?}\n1090\t    N -->|Concealed groups were called — invalid| J\n1091\t    N -->|Valid concealed/exposed status| O[\"CELEBRATION SEQUENCE\"]\n1092\t    O --> P[\"1. Table dims (celebration-dim overlay)\"]\n1093\t    P --> Q[\"2. Held beat — brief pause for anticipation\"]\n1094\t    Q --> R[\"3. Winning hand fans out from player's seat toward center\"]\n1095\t    R --> S[\"4. Signature Mahjong motif plays\"]\n1096\t    S --> T[\"5. Winner's name spotlighted — voice chat erupts\"]\n1097\t    T --> U[Scoring calculated and displayed]\n1098\t    U --> V{Discard or self-drawn?}\n1099\t    V -->|Discard Mahjong| W[\"Discarder pays 2x hand value — others pay 1x each\"]\n1100\t    V -->|Self-drawn Mahjong| X[\"All 3 losers pay 2x hand value\"]\n1101\t    W --> Y[Scoreboard updates — session totals]\n1102\t    X --> Y\n1103\t    Y --> Z[\"Optional: 'Show Hands' — all players can reveal racks\"]\n1104\t    Z --> AA[Go to Rematch flow]\n1105\t```\n1106\t\n1107\t**Key UX moments:**\n1108\t- **Mahjong button always visible, always clickable** — no smart visibility. Fixed position (P4).\n1109\t- **Auto-validation before reveal** — builds trust (\"the game knows the rules\").\n1110\t- **Cancel option for invalid declarations** — forgiving of honest mistakes. Private notification, no public shame. If the player confirms invalid declaration anyway, dead hand is enforced.\n1111\t- **Concealed hand validation** — automatically checks that concealed groups weren't formed via calls.\n1112\t- **Celebration staged for all four players** — dim, beat, fan-out, motif, spotlight. Shared spectacle.\n1113\t- **Scoring transparency** — who pays what and why is clearly displayed. Discarder-pays-double shown, not hidden.\n1114\t- **Challenge button** available as safety valve — see Challenge Flow below.\n1115\t\n1116\t**Challenge Flow:**\n1117\t\n1118\tWhen Mahjong is declared and auto-validated as valid, a secondary \"Challenge\" button appears for the other three players during the celebration sequence (positioned in the action zone, `text-secondary` styling — visible but not prominent). The challenge window lasts 10 seconds, matching the celebration's scoring display phase.\n1119\t\n1120\t**Trigger:** Any non-winning player taps \"Challenge\" because they believe the declared hand doesn't match the NMJL card pattern (e.g., wrong tile grouping, concealed/exposed mismatch the auto-validator missed, or the card data itself is wrong).\n1121\t\n1122\t**Resolution flow:**\n1123\t1. Celebration pauses. All players see: \"[Player] challenged [Winner]'s Mahjong.\"\n1124\t2. The winning hand is displayed enlarged with the matched NMJL card pattern side-by-side for all four players to review.\n1125\t3. A 30-second group review window opens. Each player votes: \"Valid\" or \"Invalid.\" The challenger's vote is pre-set to \"Invalid.\"\n1126\t4. **Majority rules (3 of 4 votes).** If 3+ players vote \"Invalid,\" the Mahjong is overturned — the winner receives a dead hand for the remainder of the game (if the game continues) and scoring is reversed. If 2+ players vote \"Valid,\" the Mahjong stands and the celebration resumes.\n1127\t5. If any player doesn't vote within 30 seconds, their vote defaults to \"Valid\" (benefit of the doubt to the winner). Silence = the declaration stands.\n1128\t\n1129\t**No penalty for challenging.** The challenge exists as a trust safety valve, not a strategic tool. Frivolous challenges waste 30 seconds of social time — the group will self-regulate. If challenges become disruptive, that's a social problem (friends being annoying), not a UX problem.\n1130\t\n1131\t**UX treatment:** The challenge review is displayed inline on the game table — not a modal, not a new screen. The winning hand and card pattern are overlaid on the felt. Voting is two large buttons (\"Valid\" / \"Invalid\") in the action zone. Voice chat remains active throughout — the discussion IS the review process.\n1132\t\n1133\t**Scope:** Challenges apply ONLY to Mahjong declarations, not to calls, scoring calculations, or other game events. Auto-validation handles the vast majority of cases correctly; the challenge exists for the rare edge case where card data or validation logic has a bug.\n1134\t\n1135\t---\n1136\t\n1137\t### 6. Rematch Flow\n1138\t\n1139\tThe game ends, but game night doesn't. One tap to play again.\n1140\t\n1141\t```mermaid\n1142\tflowchart TD\n1143\t    A[Game ends — Mahjong or wall game] --> B{Mahjong or wall game?}\n1144\t    B -->|Mahjong| C[Celebration sequence completes]\n1145\t    B -->|Wall game — no winner| D[\"'Wall game — draw' displayed neutrally\"]\n1146\t    C --> E[\"Optional: 'Show Hands' prompt\"]\n1147\t    D --> E\n1148\t    E --> F{Players reveal racks?}\n1149\t    F -->|Some/all reveal| G[\"Racks displayed — 'I was ONE tile away!' social moment\"]\n1150\t    F -->|Skip| H[Proceed to scoreboard]\n1151\t    G --> H\n1152\t    H --> I[Mood transition: Playing → Lingering]\n1153\t    I --> J[\"Session scoreboard displayed — cumulative scores across games\"]\n1154\t    J --> K[Social wind-down — chat, voice, reactions active]\n1155\t    K --> L[\"'Play Again' button visible but not pushy\"]\n1156\t    L --> M{Host decision}\n1157\t    M -->|Change settings| N[\"Host adjusts timer / card year / Joker rules between games\"]\n1158\t    N --> O[\"All players see: 'Host changed [setting] to [value]'\"]\n1159\t    O --> L\n1160\t    M -->|Tap 'Play Again'| P[Dealer rotates counterclockwise — new East]\n1161\t    P --> Q[\"Mood transition: Lingering → Playing\"]\n1162\t    Q --> R[New dealing animation — tiles distribute]\n1163\t    R --> S[Charleston begins — new game]\n1164\t    M -->|End session| T[\"Host ends room — final scores displayed\"]\n1165\t    T --> U[\"Players see final session scoreboard\"]\n1166\t```\n1167\t\n1168\t**Key UX moments:**\n1169\t- **Lingering mood** — softer warm tones, generous whitespace, relaxed pace. No rush to rematch.\n1170\t- **Show hands** — optional, social, fun. Extends the social moment.\n1171\t- **Session scoreboard** — cumulative across all games. A conversation piece.\n1172\t- **Settings changeable between games** — changes broadcast to all players.\n1173\t- **Dealer rotation** — East rotates counterclockwise after each game. New East receives 14 tiles, discards first (no draw).\n1174\t- **One tap rematch** — no room recreation, no re-sharing links. Just the rhythm of game night continuing.\n1175\t\n1176\t---\n1177\t\n1178\t### Journey Patterns\n1179\t\n1180\t**Shared interaction patterns identified across all six journeys:**\n1181\t\n1182\t| Pattern | Used In | Description |\n1183\t|---|---|---|\n1184\t| **TileSelectionAction** | Charleston (select 3), Call confirmation (select matching tiles), Joker exchange (select 1) | \"Select N tiles from rack for an action\" — shared composable with progress indicator, confirm/cancel |\n1185\t| **Two-step confirm** | Discard (select + confirm), Call (click + expose), Mahjong (click + auto-validate) | Consequential actions always get a confirmation step positioned near the action |\n1186\t| **Freeze-on-action** | Call window (freezes when any call clicked), Mahjong (freezes call window) | Time-sensitive windows freeze when a player acts, preventing race conditions |\n1187\t| **State narration** | Call resolution (\"Sarah called Pung\"), skip-ahead (\"Play continues from Linda\"), courtesy pass (\"passing 2 each\"), scoring (\"Discarder pays double\") | Every state transition is visually explained to all players — the system always shows its work |\n1188\t| **Graceful degradation** | Join (A/V fallback to avatar), Reconnection (state restores), Timeout (auto-discard), Charleston disconnect (auto-pass) | Every failure path has a recovery that keeps the game moving |\n1189\t| **Mood transitions** | Join (Arriving → Playing), Game end (Playing → Lingering), Rematch (Lingering → Playing) | Visual phase shifts mark emotional arc changes — gentle crossfades, never jarring |\n1190\t| **Private-first notifications** | Invalid Mahjong (private warning), Dead hand (private indicator), Timeout (gentle nudge) | Negative states communicated privately to the affected player, never broadcast as shame |\n1191\t\n1192\t### Flow Optimization Principles\n1193\t\n1194\t1. **Minimize taps to value** — Join: 2 taps (name + join). Draw: 1 tap. Discard: 2 taps (select + confirm). Rematch: 1 tap. Every core action is 1-2 taps.\n1195\t\n1196\t2. **Never block social** — Voice chat, text chat, and reactions remain active during every flow: Charleston, call windows, celebration, scoreboard. The social layer is never gated by game state.\n1197\t\n1198\t3. **State transitions are always visible** — When play skips ahead after a call, when the dealer rotates, when a mood shifts — the UI visually narrates every transition. No unexplained jumps.\n1199\t\n1200\t4. **Recovery paths are as obvious as action paths** — Cancel buttons during call confirmation, Mahjong cancel after invalid warning, social override for accidental discards. The \"undo\" is never hidden.\n1201\t\n1202\t5. **Time pressure is brief and forgiving** — The call window (3-5 seconds) is the only time-pressured moment, and it freezes the instant anyone acts. Timeouts escalate gently (nudge → auto-discard → group vote). No panic.\n1203\t\n1204\t6. **Emotional pacing varies by moment** — Not all interactions deserve the same tempo. The blind pass reveal gets a held beat. The celebration gets a staged sequence. The rematch gets breathing room. Faster isn't always better.\n1205\t\n1206\t## Component Strategy\n1207\t\n1208\t### Design System Coverage\n1209\t\n1210\t**Available from UnoCSS foundation (no custom build needed):**\n1211\t- Layout utilities (grid, flex, spacing, responsive breakpoints)\n1212\t- Color tokens and CSS custom properties (all palette values)\n1213\t- Typography role shortcuts (`text-game-critical`, `text-interactive`, etc.)\n1214\t- Animation tokens (timing, easing via CSS custom properties)\n1215\t- Focus ring and tap target utilities (`min-tap`)\n1216\t- Mood-switching CSS class mechanism\n1217\t\n1218\t**Gap: Everything visual is custom.** UnoCSS provides the utility-first foundation, but every visible component — from tiles to call buttons to the celebration overlay — is built from scratch. This is by design (Step 6 rationale: no existing component library fits this product).\n1219\t\n1220\t### Custom Component Specifications\n1221\t\n1222\t#### Tile\n1223\t\n1224\t**Purpose:** The atomic visual unit of the game. Displays a single Mahjong tile face.\n1225\t**States:** default, hover (lifts 4px), selected (lifts 8px + gold border), disabled (reduced opacity during other player's turn), face-down (back pattern)\n1226\t**Variants:** Standard (rack size ~50px wide), Small (exposed groups/discards ~30px, `tile-min-width`), Celebration (fan-out size, larger)\n1227\t**Interaction:** Tap to select (lifts), tap again to deselect. Drag to rearrange rack (10px dead zone threshold). Hover shows subtle lift on desktop.\n1228\t**Accessibility:** `role=\"button\"`, `aria-label=\"3 of Bamboo\"`, suit conveyed via shape/pattern in addition to color. Focus ring on keyboard navigation.\n1229\t\n1230\t#### TileRack\n1231\t\n1232\t**Purpose:** Displays the player's hand of 13-14 tiles in a horizontal row.\n1233\t**Content:** Ordered tiles, sort button, draw position indicator.\n1234\t**States:** Interactive (your turn — tiles selectable), Passive (other player's turn — tiles visible but not selectable), Selection mode (Charleston/call — specific tiles selectable with progress indicator)\n1235\t**Interaction:** Tap tiles to select/deselect. Drag to rearrange. Sort button reorders by suit then number. Horizontal scroll on phone when tiles exceed viewport.\n1236\t**Accessibility:** Arrow keys navigate between tiles. Enter selects. `role=\"list\"` with tile children as `role=\"listitem\"`.\n1237\t\n1238\t#### DiscardPool\n1239\t\n1240\t**Purpose:** Displays one player's discarded tiles in chronological rows at their seat position.\n1241\t**Content:** Tiles in order of discard, most recent tile highlighted briefly.\n1242\t**States:** Default, latest-discard (brief gold pulse on newest tile), call-window-active (latest discard enlarged/prominent)\n1243\t**Interaction:** View only. Tap a discard tile to see it enlarged (accessibility for small tiles on mobile).\n1244\t\n1245\t#### CallButtons\n1246\t\n1247\t**Purpose:** Time-sensitive action buttons that appear during the call window.\n1248\t**Content:** Only valid call options shown (Pung, Kong, Quint, Mahjong) plus Pass.\n1249\t**States:** Available (bold, colored), Frozen (dimmed after any player clicks — shows \"Resolving...\"), Hidden (no call window active)\n1250\t**Interaction:** Single tap to call. Appears instantly in fixed action zone. 44px minimum height, 20px minimum text.\n1251\t**Accessibility:** `aria-live=\"assertive\"` announces call window opening. Auto-focus on first call button for keyboard users.\n1252\t\n1253\t#### MahjongButton\n1254\t\n1255\t**Purpose:** Persistent button to declare Mahjong. Always visible, always clickable.\n1256\t**Content:** \"Mahjong\" label.\n1257\t**States:** Default (gold accent, prominent), Pressed (depressed + pulse), Disabled (never — always clickable per GDD)\n1258\t**Interaction:** Single tap triggers auto-validation flow. Fixed position in action zone (P4).\n1259\t**Accessibility:** `aria-label=\"Declare Mahjong\"`. Keyboard: Enter or Space to activate.\n1260\t\n1261\t#### PlayerPresence\n1262\t\n1263\t**Purpose:** Displays a player at their seat position — video frame or avatar fallback.\n1264\t**Content:** Video stream (when available), avatar circle with initial (fallback), player name, speaking indicator, exposed groups below.\n1265\t**States:** Default, Active turn (gold border glow), Speaking (animated indicator), Reconnecting (\"Reconnecting...\" label), Disconnected/Dead seat\n1266\t**Variants:** Large (~140x96px video on desktop), Medium (~120x80px on iPad), Small (~40px avatar on phone)\n1267\t**Interaction:** View only during gameplay.\n1268\t\n1269\t#### WallCounter\n1270\t\n1271\t**Purpose:** Shows remaining tiles in the wall. Creates organic tension.\n1272\t**Content:** \"Wall: NN\" with tile count.\n1273\t**States:** Normal (`wall-normal`), Warning (≤20 tiles, `wall-warning` amber), Critical (≤10 tiles, `wall-critical`)\n1274\t**Accessibility:** `aria-live=\"polite\"` announces state changes (normal → warning → critical).\n1275\t\n1276\t#### NMJLCardPanel\n1277\t\n1278\t**Purpose:** Displays NMJL card hand patterns for reference during play.\n1279\t**Content:** All hand patterns with notation, point values, concealed/exposed markers. Achievable hands highlighted via hand guidance.\n1280\t**States:** Open (slide-in panel on desktop, overlay on mobile), Closed, Charleston mode (positioned to keep rack visible)\n1281\t**Variants:** Slide-in panel (desktop/iPad, ~280px from right), Full-screen overlay (phone), Split-view (mobile during Charleston — card top, rack bottom)\n1282\t**Interaction:** Toggle open/close. Scroll through patterns. Tap a pattern for enlarged detail view.\n1283\t\n1284\t#### CharlestonZone\n1285\t\n1286\t**Purpose:** Manages the Charleston passing interaction — direction indicator, tile selection, pass button.\n1287\t**Content:** Direction arrow (Right/Across/Left), selected tiles preview, progress indicator (\"2 of 3\"), Pass button, blind pass lock indicator.\n1288\t**States:** Selecting (choosing tiles), Waiting (tiles selected, waiting for others), Receiving (animation of incoming tiles), Blind-locked (Across tiles hidden during blind pass), Vote (second Charleston prompt), Courtesy (0-3 tile negotiation)\n1289\t**Interaction:** Uses TileSelectionAction for tile selection. Pass button confirms. Vote buttons for second Charleston.\n1290\t\n1291\t#### CelebrationOverlay\n1292\t\n1293\t**Purpose:** The Mahjong declaration celebration sequence — dim, beat, fan-out, spotlight, motif.\n1294\t**Content:** Winning hand fanned out, winner's name, hand pattern name and point value, scoring breakdown.\n1295\t**States:** Sequence phases: Dim → Beat → Fan-out → Spotlight → Scoring → Fade to scoreboard\n1296\t**Interaction:** View only. Voice chat remains active throughout. Tapping anywhere does NOT dismiss early — the celebration plays for all four players.\n1297\t\n1298\t#### ScoreBoard\n1299\t\n1300\t**Purpose:** Session scoreboard between games — cumulative scores, game results, rematch option.\n1301\t**Content:** Player names, per-game scores, session totals, hand values, \"Show Hands\" toggle, \"Play Again\" button, settings access (host only).\n1302\t**States:** Active (between games, interactive), Final (session ended, view only)\n1303\t**Interaction:** Show Hands toggle, Play Again button (host), End Session button (host).\n1304\t\n1305\t#### SlideInPanel\n1306\t\n1307\t**Purpose:** Shared panel architecture for NMJL card and chat — slide-in from right on desktop, slide-up from bottom on mobile.\n1308\t**Content:** Configurable content slot.\n1309\t**States:** Open, Closed, Animating (slide in/out). Mutually exclusive with other SlideInPanel instances.\n1310\t**Interaction:** Toggle open/close. Opening one closes the other. Width: ~280px. Animation: `timing-tactile`, `ease-tactile`. Reactions hide when any panel is open.\n1311\t\n1312\t#### TileSelectionAction (Composable)\n1313\t\n1314\t**Purpose:** Shared interaction pattern for \"select N tiles from rack for an action.\"\n1315\t**Content:** Selection state, progress indicator (\"2 of 3 selected\"), confirm/cancel buttons.\n1316\t**Used by:** Charleston (select 3 to pass), Call confirmation (select tiles to expose), Joker exchange (select 1 matching tile).\n1317\t**States:** Selecting (progress updates), Complete (N tiles selected, confirm enabled), Cancelled (reset selection)\n1318\t**Interaction:** Tap tiles in rack to select/deselect. Progress indicator updates. Confirm/cancel always visible.\n1319\t\n1320\t### Component Implementation Strategy\n1321\t\n1322\t**Extraction-first approach:** Do NOT build shared primitives in isolation. Build the first 3-4 feature components (Tile, TileRack, DiscardPool, CallButtons), then extract shared primitives (BaseButton, BasePanel, BaseBadge, BaseToast, BaseOverlay, BaseInput, BaseToggle) as a dedicated refactoring story before Epic 5A closes. Primitives derived from real components are better than primitives imagined in advance.\n1323\t\n1324\t**Feature components built per epic:**\n1325\t\n1326\t| Epic | Components Built | Dependencies |\n1327\t|---|---|---|\n1328\t| **5A: Core Game UI** | Tile, TileRack, DiscardPool, CallButtons, MahjongButton, ScoreBoard, GameTable layout, TurnIndicator, WallCounter, PlayerPresence (avatar mode) → then extract shared primitives | None — this is the foundation |\n1329\t| **3B: Charleston** | CharlestonZone, DirectionIndicator, TileSelectionAction composable | Tile, TileRack, BaseButton |\n1330\t| **6A: Chat & Reactions** | ChatPanel (using SlideInPanel), ChatMessage, ReactionBar, ReactionBubble | SlideInPanel, BaseButton |\n1331\t| **5B: Remaining UI** | NMJLCardPanel (using SlideInPanel), HandGuidanceHighlight, SettingsPanel, RematchButton | SlideInPanel, BaseButton, BaseToggle |\n1332\t| **6B: Voice/Video** | PlayerPresence (video mode), VideoThumbnail, TalkingIndicator, AVControls | PlayerPresence (avatar) |\n1333\t| **7: Visual Polish** | CelebrationOverlay, FeltTexture, MoodTransition, AudioControls | All prior components |\n1334\t\n1335\t### Implementation Roadmap\n1336\t\n1337\t**Phase 1 — Epic 5A (Core Game UI):** Ship playable game with all core interaction components. This phase covers the Turn Cycle, Calling, and Mahjong Declaration journeys. Avatar-only player presence (video deferred to 6B). NMJL card deferred to 5B. Extract shared primitives before closing.\n1338\t\n1339\t**Phase 2 — Epics 3B + 6A (Charleston + Social):** Ship Charleston and chat/reactions. This phase completes the Charleston journey and adds the social layer. TileSelectionAction composable built here, retroactively usable in call confirmation.\n1340\t\n1341\t**Phase 3 — Epic 5B (Reference + Settings):** Ship NMJL card panel, hand guidance, wall counter states, settings. Completes the \"reference mode\" experience. SlideInPanel architecture shared with chat.\n1342\t\n1343\t**Phase 4 — Epics 6B + 7 (Polish):** Ship video, celebration, mood transitions, audio. The full emotional experience. PlayerPresence upgrades from avatar to video mode.\n1344\t\n1345\t## UX Consistency Patterns\n1346\t\n1347\t### Button Hierarchy\n1348\t\n1349\t**Four-tier button system applied consistently across all interactions:**\n1350\t\n1351\t| Tier | Style | Usage | Examples |\n1352\t|---|---|---|---|\n1353\t| **Primary** | Gold accent fill, `text-primary` (dark text), `text-game-critical` | The ONE action the player should take right now | Mahjong button, Discard confirm, Pass (Charleston), Play Again |\n1354\t| **Urgent** | `state-call-window` fill, white text, `text-game-critical` | Time-sensitive calls during the call window | Pung, Kong, Quint, Mahjong (during call window) |\n1355\t| **Secondary** | Chrome surface fill, `text-primary`, border | Supporting actions that aren't the primary path | Pass (call window), Sort, Settings, Show Hands |\n1356\t| **Tertiary** | Transparent, `text-on-felt` or `text-primary`, subtle border | Low-priority or toggle actions | NMJL card toggle, Chat toggle, A/V controls |\n1357\t\n1358\t**Button rules:**\n1359\t- Every screen has at most ONE primary (gold) button — the action the player should most likely take\n1360\t- Urgent buttons ONLY appear during the call window (3-5 seconds) — never elsewhere\n1361\t- All buttons are 44px minimum height with `text-interactive` or `text-game-critical` sizing\n1362\t- Button text is always a verb or action: \"Discard,\" \"Pass,\" \"Pung\" — never vague labels like \"OK\" or \"Submit\"\n1363\t- Disabled buttons are removed from the DOM, not grayed out. If you can't do it, you don't see it. (Exception: Mahjong button is always visible per GDD.)\n1364\t- The action zone maintains a FIXED height and width regardless of how many buttons are displayed. When fewer buttons appear (e.g., only \"Pass\" when no valid calls exist), they center within the fixed zone. The zone itself never resizes or repositions — this preserves P4 (\"same place, every time\") and prevents visual shifting.\n1365\t\n1366\t### Feedback Patterns\n1367\t\n1368\t**Immediate Acknowledgment (every interaction):**\n1369\tEvery player input gets instant visual feedback BEFORE the server responds:\n1370\t- **Tile tap:** Tile lifts from touch point (120ms, `timing-tactile`)\n1371\t- **Button press:** Button depresses with subtle scale (120ms)\n1372\t- **Panel toggle:** Panel begins slide animation immediately (120ms)\n1373\t\n1374\tThis is NOT optimistic updates — game state doesn't change until server confirms. The acknowledgment says \"I heard you,\" not \"it's done.\"\n1375\t\n1376\t**Degraded network fallback:** If server confirmation doesn't arrive within 800ms after tactile acknowledgment, show a subtle processing state on the element — a gentle pulse on the lifted tile or pressed button, not a spinner. This bridges the gap between \"instant acknowledgment\" and \"the player thinks it broke\" on flaky connections. 800ms is long enough that normal latency resolves before it triggers, short enough that no player waits more than a second without secondary feedback. If confirmation still hasn't arrived after 3 seconds, escalate to an inline \"Reconnecting...\" message.\n1377\t\n1378\t**State Narration (game events):**\n1379\tAll game state changes are visually explained to all players:\n1380\t\n1381\t| Event | Narration | Visibility |\n1382\t|---|---|---|\n1383\t| Call resolved | \"Sarah called Pung\" + priority explanation if multiple calls | All players |\n1384\t| Turn skip after call | Turn indicator moves to caller, skipped players visually passed over | All players |\n1385\t| Charleston direction change | Direction arrow animates to new direction | All players |\n1386\t| Courtesy pass resolution | \"Passing 2 each\" with count explanation | Both involved players |\n1387\t| Scoring breakdown | \"Discarder pays double\" with specific amounts | All players |\n1388\t| Settings change | \"Host changed timer to 20 seconds\" | All players |\n1389\t\n1390\t**Success Feedback:**\n1391\t- `state-success` green, brief and quiet\n1392\t- Tile successfully discarded: clack sound + tile animates to pool\n1393\t- Call confirmed: snap sound + tiles animate to exposed group\n1394\t- Mahjong validated: full celebration sequence\n1395\t- No modal success messages. The animation IS the feedback.\n1396\t\n1397\t**Error Feedback:**\n1398\t- `state-error` soft coral, private and gentle\n1399\t- Invalid Mahjong: private notification with cancel option, never broadcast\n1400\t- Invalid call group: auto-retraction, brief \"Group invalid — call retracted\" inline message\n1401\t- No matching tile for Joker exchange: \"You need a 3-Bam to exchange\" inline\n1402\t- Never use modals for errors. Inline messages near the action point, auto-dismiss after 3 seconds.\n1403\t\n1404\t**Warning Feedback:**\n1405\t- `state-warning` warm amber\n1406\t- Turn timeout approaching: gentle \"It's your turn!\" nudge\n1407\t- Wall counter state change: color shift (normal → warning → critical), no interruptive notification\n1408\t- Reconnecting player: \"Sarah is reconnecting...\" at their seat position\n1409\t\n1410\t**Information Feedback:**\n1411\t- Neutral tone, no urgency\n1412\t- Host setting changes: brief toast, auto-dismiss 3 seconds\n1413\t- Sound toggle confirmation: \"Sound is on\" toast\n1414\t- Never stack more than 1 toast on phone, 2 on tablet/desktop\n1415\t\n1416\t### Overlay & Panel Patterns\n1417\t\n1418\t**SlideInPanel (NMJL card and chat):**\n1419\t- **Desktop/iPad:** Slides in from right edge, ~280px wide, overlays the felt\n1420\t- **Mobile:** NMJL slides up as full-screen overlay; chat slides up as partial-height panel (rack visible)\n1421\t- **Mutual exclusivity:** Opening one closes the other. No stacking.\n1422\t- **Reactions hide** when any panel is open (play mode vs. reference mode)\n1423\t- **Animation:** `timing-tactile` (120ms), `ease-tactile` for open/close\n1424\t- **Backdrop:** Semi-transparent on mobile overlays so table context is preserved\n1425\t\n1426\t**Full-screen overlays (celebration, NMJL on phone):**\n1427\t- **Celebration:** Not dismissable — plays for all four players. Voice chat stays active.\n1428\t- **NMJL on phone:** Dismissable via tap outside, back gesture, or close button. During Charleston: split-view (card top, rack bottom).\n1429\t\n1430\t**No modals.** Mahjong Night does not use modal dialogs for any gameplay interaction. Confirmations are inline (discard confirm in the fixed action zone, call confirm via tile selection). The only modal-like elements are the celebration overlay (not dismissable) and the full-screen NMJL card on phone (dismissable). Modals interrupt rhythm (P2).\n1431\t\n1432\t### Turn State Communication\n1433\t\n1434\t**The three questions every player must be able to answer at a glance:**\n1435\t\n1436\t1. **\"Whose turn is it?\"**\n1437\t   - Active player's seat area has `state-turn-active` warm glow\n1438\t   - Turn indicator badge shows player name\n1439\t   - On iPad, visible from across the room on a propped-up device\n1440\t\n1441\t2. **\"What can I do right now?\"**\n1442\t   - **Your turn:** Rack is interactive (tiles selectable), action buttons visible\n1443\t   - **Not your turn:** Rack is passive (tiles visible, not selectable), no action buttons except Mahjong (always visible)\n1444\t   - **Call window:** Call buttons appear in fixed zone with valid options only\n1445\t   - **Charleston:** TileSelectionAction active with direction indicator and progress\n1446\t\n1447\t3. **\"What just happened?\"**\n1448\t   - State narration (see Feedback Patterns) explains every transition\n1449\t   - Latest discard gets a brief gold pulse in the discard pool\n1450\t   - Called tiles animate visibly from discard pool to caller's exposed area\n1451\t   - Skipped turns are visually narrated (turn indicator passes over skipped seats)\n1452\t\n1453\t### Notification Patterns\n1454\t\n1455\t**Three notification channels, never mixed:**\n1456\t\n1457\t| Channel | Mechanism | Duration | Use Cases |\n1458\t|---|---|---|---|\n1459\t| **Inline** | Text near the action point | 3 seconds auto-dismiss | Joker exchange result, invalid group retraction, courtesy pass count |\n1460\t| **Toast** | Bottom-edge or top-edge notification bar | 3 seconds auto-dismiss | Settings changes, sound toggle, reconnection status |\n1461\t| **Seat-position** | Indicator at a player's seat area | Persistent until state changes | Turn indicator, reconnecting status, speaking indicator |\n1462\t\n1463\t**Notification rules:**\n1464\t- Maximum 1 toast on phone, 2 on tablet/desktop\n1465\t- When a new toast would exceed the maximum, the newest toast replaces the oldest (FIFO). No queue. If information is important enough to persist, it belongs in an inline or seat-position notification, not a toast.\n1466\t- Toasts never overlap the rack or action buttons\n1467\t- Inline messages appear near the element that triggered them (e.g., Joker exchange message near the exposed group)\n1468\t- Private notifications (invalid Mahjong, dead hand) are ONLY inline on the affected player's view — never broadcast\n1469\t- No notification sound effects except turn ping (\"it's your turn\") — all other notifications are visual only to avoid competing with voice chat\n1470\t\n1471\t### Recent Activity Indicator\n1472\t\n1473\tA subtle game-state ticker near the turn indicator showing the last 2-3 game events in compressed form: \"Linda discarded 8-Dot → Sarah called Pung → Sarah discarded North.\" Designed for players who look away from the screen (sip of coffee, answer a question, pet the dog) and need to re-orient at a glance. Fades after 10 seconds of no new events. This is not chat — it's a broadcast-style \"what happened\" summary.\n1474\t\n1475\tVisually lightweight: `text-secondary` sizing, low opacity, positioned to not compete with primary game elements. Reads from the existing game event stream — the same WebSocket events that update the board, discard pools, and exposed groups also feed the ticker. No separate system or additional infrastructure.\n1476\t\n1477\t### Social Override Pattern\n1478\t\n1479\t**When to use:** When a player makes an accidental discard or mistaken call, and the group wants to forgive it (per GDD Social Override rules).\n1480\t\n1481\t**Trigger:** A \"Request Undo\" button appears briefly after a discard, visible only before the next irreversible game state change (next draw or resolved call). Small, secondary-styled, positioned near the discard pool.\n1482\t\n1483\t**Vote:** Other 3 players see an inline prompt at the bottom of their screen: \"[Player] requests undo — 👍 / 👎\". Requires unanimous approval (3/3). Auto-dismisses after 10 seconds. Silence = deny.\n1484\t\n1485\t**During vote:** The pending discard subtly pulses in the discard pool, signaling \"this action is in question.\" Game state is frozen until vote resolves or times out.\n1486\t\n1487\t**Tone:** The entire interaction should feel like a friend saying \"oops, can I take that back?\" — warm, casual, not formal. No modal, no dramatic language. Just a quick group thumbs-up.\n1488\t\n1489\t**Scope:** Applies to accidental discards, mistaken calls, and Charleston passing errors only. Does NOT apply to scoring, dead hands, or Mahjong challenges.\n1490\t\n1491\t### Dead Hand Indicator\n1492\t\n1493\t**Affected player's view:** A persistent, subtle badge near their rack: \"Dead Hand\" in `text-secondary` sizing with `state-error` soft coral border. Call buttons are removed during call windows (they cannot call). Mahjong button remains visible but tapping it shows an inline message: \"Dead hand — cannot declare.\" The player continues to draw and discard normally.\n1494\t\n1495\t**Other players' view:** No dead hand indicator is shown. Other players observe the behavioral change (the dead hand player never calls) but the system never broadcasts or labels the dead hand publicly. This follows the \"never amplify negative consequences\" emotional design principle.\n1496\t\n1497\t**Duration:** Persists for the remainder of the current game. Clears automatically when a new game begins.\n1498\t\n1499\t### Host Disconnect & Migration"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JHPzXLrwyTqoxi6N3jdNCi","session_id":"e018b2a0-f3f1-40e1-98cc-69fb37f4a59e","uuid":"4292a995-8f93-4aa7-a518-18d15ac354d6","timestamp":"2026-03-28T03:09:13.864Z"}
