{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0192VJaJPP9W3KamYJvWm5ph","type":"tool_result","content":"1500\t\n1501\t**Problem:** The host role controls \"Start Game,\" \"Play Again,\" settings changes, and \"End Session.\" If the host disconnects during a 60-90 minute session, these controls become inaccessible.\n1502\t\n1503\t**Host migration rule:** If the host disconnects and does not reconnect within 30 seconds, host privileges automatically transfer to the next player in counterclockwise seat order. All players see a seat-position notification: \"Sarah disconnected — Linda is now the host.\"\n1504\t\n1505\t**Behavior by game state:**\n1506\t\n1507\t| State | Host Disconnects | Migrated Host Can... |\n1508\t|---|---|---|\n1509\t| **Lobby (Arriving)** | 30s grace period, then migrate | Start game, change settings, end room |\n1510\t| **Mid-game (Playing)** | Game continues (host is just a player). 30s grace, then migrate host role silently | Access settings between games, trigger rematch |\n1511\t| **Between games (Lingering)** | 30s grace period, then migrate | Tap \"Play Again,\" change settings, end session |\n1512\t\n1513\t**Reconnection after migration:** If the original host reconnects after migration, they rejoin as a regular player. Host role does NOT automatically return — this prevents role-bouncing on flaky connections. The current host can voluntarily transfer host back via a settings option (post-MVP scope; for MVP, migration is permanent for the session).\n1514\t\n1515\t**All four players disconnect:** Room persists on the server for 5 minutes. If any player reconnects within that window, they become host and can wait for others. After 5 minutes with zero connected players, the room is cleaned up.\n1516\t\n1517\t**UX treatment:** Host migration is communicated via a brief toast (\"Linda is now the host\") — not a modal, not a celebration, just informational. The new host sees the host-only controls (settings gear, \"Play Again\" button) appear in their UI with a subtle entrance animation.\n1518\t\n1519\t### Animation Consistency\n1520\t\n1521\t**All animations use the four token tiers — no exceptions:**\n1522\t\n1523\t| Tier | Duration | Easing | Use |\n1524\t|---|---|---|---|\n1525\t| **Tactile** | 120ms | ease-out | Tile lift, button press, panel open, rack snap, notification appear |\n1526\t| **Expressive** | 400ms | cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1) | Charleston tile glide, call tile trajectory, celebration fan-out, mood crossfade |\n1527\t| **Entrance** | 200ms | ease-out | Call buttons appearing, toast enter, reconnection indicator |\n1528\t| **Exit** | 150ms | ease-in | Call window closing, toast dismissal, panel close |\n1529\t\n1530\t**Animation rules:**\n1531\t- No raw CSS `transition` with hardcoded durations — always use tokens\n1532\t- `prefers-reduced-motion` → 0ms for ALL animations, no exceptions\n1533\t- Time-sensitive elements (call buttons) appear with `timing-entrance` (200ms), never slower\n1534\t- Celebration sequence uses `timing-expressive` for the fan-out but `timing-tactile` for the initial dim — the dim is instant context, the fan-out is the show\n1535\t\n1536\t### Empty & Loading States\n1537\t\n1538\t**Empty states (rare in this game):**\n1539\t- **Waiting room (< 4 players):** \"Waiting for friends to join...\" with player avatars at filled seats, empty seat placeholders for unfilled seats. Voice chat and text already active. Not an empty state — it's the Gathering.\n1540\t- **No chat messages:** Chat panel opens with no messages. No placeholder text — the voice chat IS the conversation. The input field is ready.\n1541\t- **No exposed groups:** No placeholder. Empty space at seat position is expected at game start.\n1542\t\n1543\t**Loading states:**\n1544\t- **Initial page load:** Instant skeleton of the Arriving mood (warm cream, seat positions, name input). No spinner.\n1545\t- **During gameplay:** NO loading states. Every tap gets instant acknowledgment via tactile animation. Server confirmation arrives after the acknowledgment, not before. If there's ever a visible loading state during gameplay, something is architecturally wrong.\n1546\t- **Reconnection:** \"Sarah is reconnecting...\" at the player's seat position. Gentle, informational, no spinner. Game continues for other players.\n1547\t\n1548\t## Responsive Design & Accessibility\n1549\t\n1550\t### Responsive Strategy\n1551\t\n1552\t**Design approach: iPad-first, adapting outward**\n1553\t\n1554\tMahjong Night is designed for iPad landscape (1024px) as the primary target, adapting upward to desktop and downward to phone. This is NOT traditional mobile-first — the primary audience uses iPads propped on kitchen tables. The desktop experience gains space; the phone experience uses progressive disclosure.\n1555\t\n1556\t**Desktop (>1024px):**\n1557\t- More breathing room for all elements — larger video frames, wider discard pools, more generous spacing\n1558\t- NMJL slide-in panel and chat slide-in panel can potentially coexist side-by-side if viewport exceeds ~1400px (design decision for implementation: test whether dual panels feel useful or cluttered)\n1559\t- Hover states available — tile hover lift, button hover highlights, tooltip on Joker identity\n1560\t- Keyboard navigation is first-class (Tab zones, Arrow keys, Enter/Escape)\n1561\t- Layout should NOT feel like a stretched tablet app — use the extra space for social and reference elements, not whitespace\n1562\t\n1563\t**iPad Landscape (~1024px) — Primary Target:**\n1564\t- The reference design. All layout decisions start here.\n1565\t- Full-width felt table (Direction B: Immersive Table)\n1566\t- Video frames at seat positions (~120x80px)\n1567\t- Rack fits 13-14 tiles at ~50px each without scrolling\n1568\t- NMJL card via slide-in panel from right (~280px)\n1569\t- Action zone centered above rack, fixed size\n1570\t- Touch-first with 44px minimum tap targets\n1571\t\n1572\t**iPad Portrait (~768px):**\n1573\t- Narrower viewport — NMJL shifts to overlay, video frames shrink (~80x60px)\n1574\t- Discard pools compress slightly\n1575\t- Rack still fits without scrolling at this width\n1576\t- Bottom bar appears for NMJL/chat/A/V toggles\n1577\t\n1578\t**Phone Landscape (~667-926px):**\n1579\t- Simplified layout — essential elements only\n1580\t- Small video avatars (~40px) with speaking indicators\n1581\t- Compressed discard pools\n1582\t- Rack may begin to scroll at lower end of range\n1583\t\n1584\t**Phone Portrait (375-430px) — Most Constrained:**\n1585\t- Full progressive disclosure — everything non-essential is one tap away\n1586\t- NMJL card: full-screen overlay\n1587\t- Chat: slide-up partial panel\n1588\t- Rack scrolls horizontally — tiles never shrink below 30px (`tile-min-width`)\n1589\t- Bottom bar for all toggles (NMJL, chat, A/V)\n1590\t- Call buttons may stack vertically when 4+ options appear simultaneously\n1591\t\n1592\t**Orientation change:** Layout adapts fluidly on device orientation change with no game state loss, no modal interruptions, and no animation restarts. The celebration sequence, if in progress, continues from its current phase — it does not restart. Panel state (NMJL open/closed) is preserved across rotation. The rack never loses tile selection state during rotation. Orientation change must be a tested scenario in every epic, not an afterthought.\n1593\t\n1594\t**Minimum table height:** The felt table center area (where discard pools and wall counter live) must never be less than 40% of the viewport height on any device. If surrounding elements (seats, action zone, rack) would compress the table below this threshold on phone portrait, the rack scrolls into view rather than being always-visible — the player scrolls down slightly to see their full rack, freeing vertical space for the table. This is a better trade-off than shrinking discard tiles below readability. Flag as a design decision to resolve during Epic 5A layout implementation.\n1595\t\n1596\t### Breakpoint Strategy\n1597\t\n1598\t**Three breakpoints, iPad-first:**\n1599\t\n1600\t| Breakpoint | Range | Layout Mode | Key Changes |\n1601\t|---|---|---|---|\n1602\t| **Desktop** | ≥1024px | Full immersive table | Slide-in panels from right, floating reactions, large video frames, hover states |\n1603\t| **Tablet** | 768px–1023px | Adapted table | NMJL as overlay, smaller video, bottom bar appears, no hover states |\n1604\t| **Phone** | <768px | Progressive disclosure | Full-screen NMJL overlay, slide-up chat, horizontal rack scroll, stacked call buttons, avatar-only seats |\n1605\t\n1606\t**Implementation approach:**\n1607\t- CSS custom properties + UnoCSS responsive utilities (`md:`, `lg:` prefixes)\n1608\t- Component-level adaptation (components read viewport and adapt internally), not page-level media queries that restructure the DOM\n1609\t- The felt surface is ALWAYS full-width at every breakpoint — no sidebar ever consumes horizontal space during gameplay\n1610\t- Test every interactive element at 375px (iPhone SE) — the minimum viable viewport\n1611\t\n1612\t**Container-based component sizing:** Component sizing for spatial elements (video frames, discard pools, exposed groups) should use container-based sizing rather than purely viewport-based breakpoints. An iPad Mini in landscape hits the 1024px Desktop breakpoint but has a physically smaller screen (~8.3 inches) than a 13-inch laptop at the same viewport width. Video frames should ask \"how much space does my seat area have?\" rather than \"how wide is the viewport?\" — using CSS container queries where supported, or parent-relative sizing as a fallback.\n1613\t\n1614\t**Call button layout at phone breakpoint (<768px):**\n1615\tWhen 4 call options appear simultaneously (Pung, Kong, Quint, Mahjong), the 44px minimum height + 8px gaps + 20px text requires ~220px of vertical or horizontal space. On phone viewports, buttons should stack in a 2x2 grid within the fixed-size action zone rather than a single row. This specific layout must be resolved during Epic 5A.\n1616\t\n1617\t### Accessibility Strategy\n1618\t\n1619\t**WCAG AA compliance — not as a checklist, but as the design itself.**\n1620\t\n1621\tFor this audience (women 40-70+), accessibility requirements ARE the core design requirements. Large text, high contrast, generous tap targets, and clear visual hierarchy aren't accommodations — they're the product.\n1622\t\n1623\t**Visual Accessibility:**\n1624\t- **Contrast:** WCAG AA minimum (4.5:1 normal text, 3:1 large text and UI components). All color token pairings pre-validated at the design system level.\n1625\t- **Text size:** 14px absolute minimum. Game-critical text 20px+. No thin/light font weights.\n1626\t- **Color independence:** Tile suits distinguished by shape/pattern AND color. Hand guidance uses gold/neutral, never suit colors. Game state never communicated by color alone.\n1627\t- **Dark mode:** System-preference responsive. Felt and gold remain constant; chrome layer inverts. Both modes meet contrast requirements independently.\n1628\t\n1629\t**Motor Accessibility:**\n1630\t- **Tap targets:** 44px minimum on all interactive elements. 8px minimum gap between adjacent targets.\n1631\t- **Drag/tap dead zone:** 10px movement threshold prevents accidental rack rearrangement from imprecise taps.\n1632\t- **Two-step confirm:** All consequential actions have a confirmation step — protects against accidental taps.\n1633\t- **No time-critical precision:** The call window (3-5 seconds) is the fastest interaction, and it freezes the instant anyone acts. No action requires fast or precise motor control.\n1634\t\n1635\t**Cognitive Accessibility:**\n1636\t- **Show, don't hide (P1):** No features hidden behind exploration or menus. Progressive disclosure via game state, not navigation.\n1637\t- **Same place, every time (P4):** Fixed element positions build spatial memory. The Mahjong button never moves.\n1638\t- **State narration:** Every game event is visually explained. No unexplained state changes.\n1639\t- **Recovery paths:** Cancel/undo options are as prominent as action buttons during recovery windows.\n1640\t- **Recent Activity Indicator:** Players who look away can re-orient at a glance.\n1641\t\n1642\t**Audio Accessibility:**\n1643\t- **Sound is additive, never required.** Every sound effect has a visual equivalent that is sufficient on its own:\n1644\t  - Tile clack → discard animation to pool\n1645\t  - Call snap → exposure animation to seat\n1646\t  - Turn ping → turn indicator glow at seat position\n1647\t  - Celebration motif → dim + fan-out + spotlight visual sequence\n1648\t- No game information is communicated ONLY through audio. For hearing-impaired players, text chat and the reaction system (👍 😂 😱 😭 🎉) serve as the accessible social channel — the visual equivalent of voice expressiveness.\n1649\t\n1650\t**Input Accessibility:**\n1651\t- **Keyboard navigation:** Full Tab zone model (Rack → Actions → NMJL → Chat → Controls). Arrow keys within zones. Enter confirms. Escape exits chat focus. Gold focus ring (2px solid, 2px offset) on every interactive element.\n1652\t- **Screen readers:** Semantic HTML (`role`, `aria-label`, `aria-live`). Tile identities announced (\"3 of Bamboo\"). Call window announced as assertive. State changes announced as polite.\n1653\t- **Reduced motion:** `prefers-reduced-motion` → 0ms for ALL animations. No exceptions. Motion for Vue handles this natively; CSS transitions reference custom properties.\n1654\t\n1655\t### Testing Strategy\n1656\t\n1657\t**Responsive Testing:**\n1658\t\n1659\t| Device | Priority | What to Validate |\n1660\t|---|---|---|\n1661\t| **iPad (landscape)** | Critical | Primary layout — all elements fit, tiles readable, video at seats, action zone positioned |\n1662\t| **iPad (portrait)** | High | NMJL shifts to overlay, bottom bar appears, video shrinks, rack still fits |\n1663\t| **iPhone SE (375px)** | High | Minimum viable viewport — rack scrolls, tiles ≥30px, call buttons stack, NMJL full-screen |\n1664\t| **iPhone 14/15 (390-430px)** | High | Common phone viewport — same as SE but slightly more room |\n1665\t| **Desktop (1440px)** | Medium | Extra space used well, not wasted. Hover states work. |\n1666\t| **Desktop (1920px)** | Low | Ultra-wide doesn't break. Max-width container prevents absurd stretching. |\n1667\t\n1668\t**Browser testing:** Chrome, Safari (critical — iPad default), Firefox, Edge. Latest two versions. Safari on iOS is the single most important browser for this audience.\n1669\t\n1670\t**Accessibility Testing:**\n1671\t\n1672\t| Test | Tool/Method | Frequency |\n1673\t|---|---|---|\n1674\t| **Contrast ratios** | axe-core or Lighthouse CI | Every PR (automated) |\n1675\t| **Keyboard navigation** | Manual testing | Every new component |\n1676\t| **Screen reader** | VoiceOver (macOS/iOS) | Per epic completion |\n1677\t| **Color blindness** | Chrome DevTools simulation | Per epic completion |\n1678\t| **Reduced motion** | `prefers-reduced-motion` toggle | Every animation added |\n1679\t| **Tap target sizing** | Manual measurement at 375px | Every new interactive element |\n1680\t| **Tile readability at 30px** | Render all 152 faces, test with target demographic | Epic 5A validation checkpoint |\n1681\t| **Orientation change** | Rotate device mid-game, mid-Charleston, mid-celebration | Every epic |\n1682\t\n1683\t**Tile readability validation (Epic 5A):** Render all 152 unique tile faces at 30px width (`tile-min-width`), screenshot them, and have at least one person from the target demographic (40-70+) confirm readability of suit symbols, Arabic numerals, and corner indices. If corner indices are not readable at 30px, bump to 32px or 34px before building dependent components. This is a defined test with a pass/fail criterion.\n1684\t\n1685\t**Player Testing:**\n1686\t- Test with actual target demographic (women 40-70+) — their feedback on readability, tap target comfort, and \"did you know what to do?\" is the ultimate validation\n1687\t- Include at least one tester with low vision and one with motor precision challenges\n1688\t- Test on actual iPads propped on tables at arm's length — this is the real usage scenario\n1689\t\n1690\t### Implementation Guidelines\n1691\t\n1692\t**Responsive Development:**\n1693\t- UnoCSS responsive prefixes (`md:`, `lg:`) for breakpoint-specific styles\n1694\t- Component-level viewport adaptation — components check their container size and adapt, not just the page layout\n1695\t- `rem` units for text sizing (respects user's browser font size setting)\n1696\t- `px` for tap target minimums and spacing gaps (these are physical constraints, not relative)\n1697\t- CSS `dvh` (dynamic viewport height) on mobile to account for browser chrome appearing/disappearing\n1698\t- Test touch interactions on actual touch devices — mouse simulation misses dead zone and multi-touch issues\n1699\t- Safe area insets: all fixed-bottom elements (bottom bar, rack when bottommost) must include `padding-bottom: env(safe-area-inset-bottom)` to avoid overlap with iPhone home indicator. Discard confirm button viewport boundary detection must account for `env(safe-area-inset-top)` to avoid clipping into notch/Dynamic Island on phone landscape.\n1700\t\n1701\t**Accessibility Development:**\n1702\t- Semantic HTML first — `<button>` for actions, `<nav>` for navigation, `<main>` for content. ARIA is a supplement, not a replacement.\n1703\t- `aria-live=\"assertive\"` for call window opening (time-sensitive). `aria-live=\"polite\"` for state changes, wall counter, turn indicator.\n1704\t- Focus management: when a panel opens, focus moves to the panel. When it closes, focus returns to the trigger element.\n1705\t- Skip link: \"Skip to game table\" link at top of page, visible on Tab focus. Jumps past any chrome to the rack/action area.\n1706\t- All `<img>` and SVG tile faces have descriptive `alt`/`aria-label` text. Decorative elements (felt texture, shadows) have `aria-hidden=\"true\"`.\n1707\t- Test with VoiceOver on iPad — this is the screen reader most likely to be used by the target audience.\n1708\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JHPzXLrwyTqoxi6N3jdNCi","session_id":"e018b2a0-f3f1-40e1-98cc-69fb37f4a59e","uuid":"0277338c-e987-4170-8ef9-17bf84538780","timestamp":"2026-03-28T03:09:17.979Z"}
